WEBVTT

00:01.502 --> 00:04.505
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

00:04.505 --> 00:11.512
<i>♪ ♪</i>

00:11.512 --> 00:14.890
<i>‐ Ulysses S. Grant.</i>

00:14.890 --> 00:16.558
This man's name
is U. S. Grant.

00:16.558 --> 00:19.228
<i>‐ A military life</i>
<i>had no charms for me.</i>

00:19.228 --> 00:22.356
<i>‐ Grant, you know</i>
<i>the rules about drink.</i>

00:22.356 --> 00:25.108
<i>Resign or court‐martial.</i>

00:25.108 --> 00:27.236
<i>‐ I'm not asking you to speak.</i>

00:27.236 --> 00:29.238
I'm asking you to lead.

00:29.238 --> 00:31.031
<i>‐ There were</i>
<i>but two parties now,</i>

00:31.031 --> 00:33.700
<i>traitors and patriots.</i>

00:33.700 --> 00:35.619
I believe
if I can take both forts,

00:35.619 --> 00:38.163
we can advance
as far as Nashville.

00:38.163 --> 00:40.832
‐ When I wish to consult you
on the subject,

00:40.832 --> 00:43.126
I will notify you.

00:43.126 --> 00:44.461
<i>‐ General Buell's men?</i>

00:44.461 --> 00:45.712
‐ They're three days out.

00:45.712 --> 00:47.756
‐ We'll move on Corinth
when he gets here.

00:47.756 --> 00:50.884
<i>There is little doubt</i>
<i>that Corinth will fall easily.</i>

00:50.884 --> 00:52.678
[gunshot]

00:52.678 --> 00:53.929
‐ Fire!

00:53.929 --> 00:57.182
[gunfire, soldiers clamoring]

00:57.182 --> 01:01.311
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:01.311 --> 01:02.813
‐ Come on, now, boys, pitch in.

01:02.813 --> 01:04.356
I'm right behind you.

01:04.356 --> 01:05.899
[soldiers yelling]

01:05.899 --> 01:09.069
‐ Fire the cannon!
[cannon booms]

01:09.069 --> 01:16.076
<i>♪ ♪</i>

01:17.411 --> 01:22.165
<i>‐ Very few people really know</i>
<i>who Ulysses S. Grant was.</i>

01:22.165 --> 01:26.712
<i>‐ Today there is this sense</i>
<i>that he's forgotten.</i>

01:26.712 --> 01:29.965
<i>‐ He's been called</i>
<i>so many things over the years.</i>

01:29.965 --> 01:32.593
<i>‐ The greatest general</i>
<i>of his time.</i>

01:32.593 --> 01:34.803
<i>‐ A military genius.</i>

01:34.803 --> 01:36.638
<i>‐ A bloody butcher.</i>

01:36.638 --> 01:38.640
<i>‐ A corrupt president.</i>

01:38.640 --> 01:41.685
<i>‐ A belligerent drunk</i>
<i>who got lucky.</i>

01:42.477 --> 01:44.771
He didn't get lucky.

01:44.771 --> 01:47.733
<i>‐ Ulysses S. Grant</i>
<i>is this perfectly average,</i>

01:47.733 --> 01:51.695
humble individual from a poor,
hardscrabble background.

01:51.695 --> 01:54.948
<i>‐ With a lot of hard times</i>
<i>and failures in his life.</i>

01:54.948 --> 01:57.159
‐ But he's got
this dogged determination,

01:57.159 --> 01:59.828
<i>this bulldog mentality.</i>

01:59.828 --> 02:01.455
‐ This guy comes from nothing,

02:01.455 --> 02:02.789
<i>rises to the highest ranks</i>

02:02.789 --> 02:04.624
<i>of the Union army.</i>

02:04.624 --> 02:07.252
<i>‐ Fights bloody,</i>
<i>terrible battles.</i>

02:07.252 --> 02:09.838
<i>‐ With indomitable will.</i>

02:09.838 --> 02:11.048
‐ To save the Union.

02:11.048 --> 02:12.966
<i>‐ To heal his country.</i>

02:12.966 --> 02:17.012
<i>‐ To lead the nation</i>
<i>towards justice for everybody.</i>

02:17.012 --> 02:19.473
<i>‐ He's the unheroic hero</i>

02:19.473 --> 02:22.601
<i>of our greatest national epic,</i>
<i>the American Civil War.</i>

02:22.601 --> 02:25.103
<i>‐ It's truly</i>
<i>an American story</i>

02:25.103 --> 02:27.522
<i>not only of patriotism</i>
<i>to the nation</i>

02:27.522 --> 02:29.566
<i>but for the values,</i>
<i>who we are,</i>

02:29.566 --> 02:31.818
<i>and who we aspire to be.</i>

02:31.818 --> 02:35.822
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:38.283 --> 02:45.290
<i>♪ ♪</i>

02:46.333 --> 02:48.585
<i>‐ Dear Julia...</i>

02:48.585 --> 02:50.921
<i>the battle at this place</i>
<i>was the most desperate</i>

02:50.921 --> 02:53.840
<i>that has ever taken place</i>
<i>on the continent,</i>

02:53.840 --> 02:56.843
<i>and I don't look</i>
<i>for another like it.</i>

02:56.843 --> 03:03.850
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:13.694 --> 03:15.779
<i>‐ The battle of Shiloh</i>
<i>is the bloodiest battle</i>

03:15.779 --> 03:18.240
<i>in American history</i>
<i>up to that time.</i>

03:18.240 --> 03:19.366
The nation is shocked

03:19.366 --> 03:21.201
when the casualty reports
come out.

03:21.201 --> 03:23.912
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:23.912 --> 03:27.249
<i>‐ Grant doesn't come out</i>
<i>of Shiloh looking very good.</i>

03:27.249 --> 03:29.709
You know, he was
"Unconditional Surrender" Grant

03:29.709 --> 03:31.086
at Fort Donelson,

03:31.086 --> 03:32.754
became a hero.

03:32.754 --> 03:35.006
And now all of a sudden,
people are asking,

03:35.006 --> 03:37.592
<i>"What happened?"</i>

03:37.592 --> 03:40.095
<i>‐ The casualty list</i>
<i>and the fact that Grant</i>

03:40.095 --> 03:42.973
was surprised on the first day

03:42.973 --> 03:46.351
overshadow the fact
of the victory.

03:46.351 --> 03:48.311
<i>♪ ♪</i>

03:48.311 --> 03:50.605
<i>‐ Rumors start</i>
<i>reaching Washington</i>

03:50.605 --> 03:52.983
that explain that surprise
as Grant must be

03:52.983 --> 03:54.734
on the bottle once again.

03:54.734 --> 03:56.778
<i>But the president answered</i>

03:56.778 --> 03:59.322
<i>those critical of Grant</i>
<i>by saying,</i>

03:59.322 --> 04:01.992
<i>"I can't spare this man.</i>

04:01.992 --> 04:03.952
<i>He fights."</i>

04:03.952 --> 04:11.001
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:12.586 --> 04:15.672
[insects chirping]

04:15.672 --> 04:18.467
<i>‐ After the bloodbath</i>
<i>of Shiloh...</i>

04:18.467 --> 04:20.760
<i>Grant's superior,</i>

04:20.760 --> 04:22.637
<i>Henry W. Halleck,</i>

04:22.637 --> 04:25.599
<i>removes Grant</i>
<i>from his army command...</i>

04:25.599 --> 04:28.435
with no duties,

04:28.435 --> 04:30.479
no real authority, nothing.

04:30.479 --> 04:32.105
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:32.105 --> 04:35.317
<i>‐ Grant is so frustrated</i>
<i>by this.</i>

04:35.317 --> 04:37.194
<i>Halleck is not aggressive,</i>

04:37.194 --> 04:38.487
and then you have
someone like Grant,

04:38.487 --> 04:39.946
who is very go‐get‐'em.

04:39.946 --> 04:42.324
He's ready to jump in,
grab the initiative.

04:42.324 --> 04:44.284
<i>Grant wants to finish off</i>

04:44.284 --> 04:46.119
<i>what's left</i>
<i>of the Confederate army</i>

04:46.119 --> 04:47.788
<i>that attacked him at Shiloh</i>

04:47.788 --> 04:50.332
<i>but are having time</i>
<i>to reorganize themselves</i>

04:50.332 --> 04:53.293
<i>as they fall back</i>
<i>into Corinth.</i>

04:53.293 --> 04:56.880
<i>♪ ♪</i>

04:56.880 --> 04:59.925
<i>‐</i> They're well defended.

04:59.925 --> 05:02.636
I would say quite active.

05:02.636 --> 05:04.971
They're preparing for battle.

05:04.971 --> 05:08.225
‐ Respectfully,
General Halleck, that smoke?

05:08.225 --> 05:11.478
It's plain.
They're burning supplies.

05:11.478 --> 05:14.231
It suggests they're preparing
to retreat, sir.

05:14.231 --> 05:17.108
[train horn blowing]

05:18.693 --> 05:20.195
‐ Hear that?

05:20.195 --> 05:22.155
I knew it.

05:22.155 --> 05:24.032
Trains coming in every day.

05:24.032 --> 05:25.909
They're reinforcing.

05:25.909 --> 05:29.704
‐ Again, sir, I differ.
This is a retreat.

05:29.704 --> 05:32.332
Our railroad men
have ears on the tracks.

05:32.332 --> 05:33.750
They say it's empty trains
coming in

05:33.750 --> 05:35.877
and loaded ones going out.

05:35.877 --> 05:38.505
They're withdrawing.

05:38.505 --> 05:39.506
Let's move on them now‐‐

05:39.506 --> 05:41.925
‐ Enough, Grant.

05:41.925 --> 05:46.513
After Shiloh, I'd have thought
you'd have learned your lesson.

05:46.513 --> 05:52.644
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:52.644 --> 05:55.689
‐ Grant is like, "Speed,
tempo‐‐these are weapons

05:55.689 --> 05:58.316
that can be used for an
adversary that's on the run."

05:58.316 --> 05:59.609
<i>♪ ♪</i>

05:59.609 --> 06:02.529
<i>Grant recognizes</i>
<i>there's an opportunity,</i>

06:02.529 --> 06:04.281
<i>but he also knows</i>
<i>the windows of opportunity</i>

06:04.281 --> 06:05.866
<i>are very small,</i>

06:05.866 --> 06:07.075
and if you don't
take advantage of them,

06:07.075 --> 06:09.244
they'll pass you by.

06:09.244 --> 06:12.539
<i>And Grant sees this</i>
<i>as a missed opportunity.</i>

06:12.539 --> 06:14.374
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:14.374 --> 06:16.334
‐ General.

06:16.334 --> 06:23.341
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:26.720 --> 06:28.179
‐ Rebs are gone.

06:28.179 --> 06:30.390
Nothing but a bunch
of scarecrows.

06:30.390 --> 06:31.558
<i>♪ ♪</i>

06:31.558 --> 06:34.352
‐ Send a telegraph
to the president.

06:34.352 --> 06:36.688
Corinth is ours.

06:36.688 --> 06:39.774
It's a great Union victory.

06:39.774 --> 06:44.613
<i>‐ The possession of Corinth</i>
<i>was of strategic importance,</i>

06:44.613 --> 06:47.991
<i>but the victory was barren</i>
<i>in every other particular.</i>

06:47.991 --> 06:51.620
<i>Corinth had already</i>
<i>been evacuated.</i>

06:51.620 --> 06:54.623
<i>A well‐directed attack</i>
<i>would at least have partially</i>

06:54.623 --> 06:56.374
<i>destroyed the defending army.</i>

06:56.374 --> 07:00.211
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:00.211 --> 07:02.088
<i>‐ Corinth has fallen.</i>
<i>Grant is like,</i>

07:02.088 --> 07:03.965
"Great, this is an opportunity
to strike out.

07:03.965 --> 07:05.800
We should go to Atlanta.
We should go to Vicksburg."

07:05.800 --> 07:07.844
And what happens?
Halleck sits tight.

07:07.844 --> 07:09.429
He disperses the army,

07:09.429 --> 07:11.598
and things slow down
in the western theater.

07:11.598 --> 07:13.308
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:13.308 --> 07:16.311
<i>‐ Keep in mind that</i>
<i>in the early years of the war,</i>

07:16.311 --> 07:19.981
<i>there are really</i>
<i>two distinct theaters.</i>

07:19.981 --> 07:22.984
<i>The west is</i>
<i>where Grant is.</i>

07:22.984 --> 07:25.236
<i>And there's</i>
<i>the eastern theater,</i>

07:25.236 --> 07:28.198
<i>and this is the fights</i>
<i>of the Union army</i>

07:28.198 --> 07:32.118
against essentially the Army
of Northern Virginia of Lee.

07:32.118 --> 07:33.787
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:33.787 --> 07:37.290
<i>‐ So while Grant</i>
<i>has been demoted out west,</i>

07:37.290 --> 07:39.042
<i>in the east,</i>
<i>Robert E. Lee</i>

07:39.042 --> 07:41.836
<i>has taken over</i>
<i>the Army of Northern Virginia.</i>

07:41.836 --> 07:43.713
And the average result
in the eastern theater

07:43.713 --> 07:46.383
is that
the Union army loses

07:46.383 --> 07:49.511
<i>to an undermanned</i>
<i>Confederate army.</i>

07:49.511 --> 07:51.513
<i>♪ ♪</i>

07:51.513 --> 07:54.224
<i>‐</i> In the east, Lincoln's
experience with his generals

07:54.224 --> 07:59.187
had been bad,
trending to worse.

07:59.187 --> 08:02.023
<i>‐ Abraham Lincoln had seen</i>
<i>Robert E. Lee defeat</i>

08:02.023 --> 08:04.693
an entire bench
of Union commanders.

08:04.693 --> 08:06.236
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:06.236 --> 08:09.489
<i>‐ By this time, Grant</i>
<i>is in a bad situation too.</i>

08:09.489 --> 08:13.118
<i>That second year of the war</i>
<i>is just not very good for him.</i>

08:13.118 --> 08:14.828
In fact, he calls it,
of course,

08:14.828 --> 08:16.329
the darkest days of the war.

08:16.329 --> 08:19.082
[soldiers clamoring]

08:19.082 --> 08:23.795
<i>‐ Dear Julia,</i>
<i>I am no longer boss.</i>

08:23.795 --> 08:26.840
<i>What the next move is</i>
<i>or the part I am to take,</i>

08:26.840 --> 08:28.675
<i>I do not know.</i>

08:28.675 --> 08:32.846
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:32.846 --> 08:34.639
‐ What's going on?

08:34.639 --> 08:36.141
‐ I've had enough.

08:36.141 --> 08:37.350
<i>♪ ♪</i>

08:37.350 --> 08:38.601
I'm resigning.

08:38.601 --> 08:40.311
‐ Oh, for God's sake.

08:40.311 --> 08:42.355
‐ Look, I want to fight
and win this war,

08:42.355 --> 08:44.441
but if Halleck
has me sit it out,

08:44.441 --> 08:46.651
I might as well
sit it out at home.

08:46.651 --> 08:48.862
‐ You're not resigning.

08:48.862 --> 08:51.072
‐ If I can't fight,
well, then I'm useless.

08:51.072 --> 08:54.409
‐ Sam, you're the most useful
man we have.

08:54.409 --> 08:57.078
I know it. You know‐‐
By God, Lincoln?

08:57.078 --> 08:58.204
He knows it.

08:58.204 --> 09:01.875
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:01.875 --> 09:02.876
‐ Look at this.

09:02.876 --> 09:06.087
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:06.087 --> 09:08.965
It says I was drunk
at Shiloh.

09:08.965 --> 09:10.258
‐ Oh, hell.

09:10.258 --> 09:12.093
Forget the papers.

09:12.093 --> 09:15.847
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:18.433 --> 09:20.602
Listen.

09:20.602 --> 09:23.730
You know the next move
is Vicksburg.

09:23.730 --> 09:25.732
You can take Vicksburg.

09:25.732 --> 09:27.734
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:27.734 --> 09:30.070
Who else can do it?

09:30.070 --> 09:32.072
Halleck?

09:32.072 --> 09:34.908
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:34.908 --> 09:37.077
‐ Vicksburg.

09:37.077 --> 09:39.079
Lincoln was right.

09:39.079 --> 09:40.663
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:40.663 --> 09:42.707
Vicksburg is the key.

09:42.707 --> 09:49.714
<i>♪ ♪</i>

09:50.507 --> 09:54.135
<i>‐ Controlling Vicksburg</i>
<i>allowed food and other goods</i>

09:54.135 --> 09:56.429
<i>to move freely</i>
<i>across the Mississippi</i>

09:56.429 --> 09:58.181
<i>and get onto railcars</i>

09:58.181 --> 10:01.184
<i>and feed the Confederacy</i>
<i>in the east.</i>

10:01.184 --> 10:06.231
<i>Without it, the Confederacy</i>
<i>can be cut in two.</i>

10:06.231 --> 10:07.774
But for any army in history,

10:07.774 --> 10:10.401
capturing Vicksburg
would be a daunting task.

10:10.401 --> 10:13.822
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:13.822 --> 10:15.949
<i>‐ The city of Vicksburg</i>
<i>is on the east bank</i>

10:15.949 --> 10:18.159
<i>of the Mississippi River.</i>

10:18.159 --> 10:22.247
<i>And it is nestled among bluffs</i>
<i>that tower 300 feet</i>

10:22.247 --> 10:26.251
<i>above a horseshoe‐shaped bend</i>
<i>of the Mississippi.</i>

10:26.251 --> 10:30.130
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:30.130 --> 10:34.384
<i>The line of defense</i>
<i>consisted of nine major forts</i>

10:34.384 --> 10:38.096
<i>connected by a continuous line</i>
<i>of trenches and rifle pits</i>

10:38.096 --> 10:41.266
<i>that stretched for more</i>
<i>than eight miles</i>

10:41.266 --> 10:45.270
<i>and then 172 big guns.</i>

10:45.270 --> 10:48.148
<i>♪ ♪</i>

10:48.148 --> 10:50.817
<i>‐ Back east, Abraham Lincoln</i>
<i>was at that moment</i>

10:50.817 --> 10:54.404
<i>about to rid himself</i>
<i>of his general and chief</i>

10:54.404 --> 10:56.364
<i>George McClellan,</i>

10:56.364 --> 10:58.366
and the replacement
that he pitches upon

10:58.366 --> 11:00.785
is Henry Wager Halleck.

11:00.785 --> 11:03.872
<i>He brings Halleck east.</i>

11:03.872 --> 11:06.499
<i>‐ And so finally,</i>
<i>the clouds part,</i>

11:06.499 --> 11:09.169
<i>and Halleck gives Grant</i>
<i>the authority</i>

11:09.169 --> 11:11.671
<i>to command as Grant sees fit,</i>

11:11.671 --> 11:13.840
and the interesting thing is,
it takes Grant

11:13.840 --> 11:16.467
all of one day

11:16.467 --> 11:20.680
to start organizing
an offensive against Vicksburg.

11:20.680 --> 11:24.392
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:24.392 --> 11:27.437
<i>‐ I would call Grant's</i>
<i>Vicksburg campaign</i>

11:27.437 --> 11:28.938
his masterpiece.

11:28.938 --> 11:30.899
It's the centerpiece
of the war.

11:30.899 --> 11:32.609
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:32.609 --> 11:37.030
<i>But Vicksburg was incredibly</i>
<i>difficult to get at.</i>

11:37.030 --> 11:39.949
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:39.949 --> 11:42.285
<i>‐ When Grant starts</i>
<i>this campaign,</i>

11:42.285 --> 11:45.205
<i>Grant is on the western side</i>
<i>of the river.</i>

11:45.205 --> 11:47.415
Vicksburg, of course, is on
the eastern side of the river.

11:47.415 --> 11:49.209
<i>♪ ♪</i>

11:49.209 --> 11:54.714
<i>‐ North of Vicksburg</i>
<i>was a great, gigantic swamp.</i>

11:54.714 --> 11:57.884
<i>He needs to put his troops</i>
<i>on open ground,</i>

11:57.884 --> 12:02.096
<i>but the only open ground</i>
<i>is below Vicksburg</i>

12:02.096 --> 12:04.849
<i>on the eastern side</i>
<i>of the river.</i>

12:04.849 --> 12:09.395
Well, how are you going
to get troops below Vicksburg?

12:09.395 --> 12:13.107
<i>You just can't send</i>
<i>transports and gunboats</i>

12:13.107 --> 12:15.944
<i>because they would have to run</i>
<i>the batteries at Vicksburg</i>

12:15.944 --> 12:17.779
<i>to get past the defenses.</i>

12:17.779 --> 12:23.576
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:23.576 --> 12:26.329
<i>‐ Now, throughout the winter,</i>
<i>Grant will orchestrate</i>

12:26.329 --> 12:29.374
a series of bayou campaigns,
as they were called.

12:29.374 --> 12:32.919
<i>♪ ♪</i>

12:32.919 --> 12:37.173
<i>‐ Grant makes seven attempts</i>
<i>to get at Vicksburg.</i>

12:37.173 --> 12:39.801
<i>All of these are efforts</i>
<i>to get around the city</i>

12:39.801 --> 12:42.178
without having to run
those batteries,

12:42.178 --> 12:44.514
which is their great fear.

12:44.514 --> 12:49.602
<i>‐ Among the operations</i>
<i>is excavation of a canal.</i>

12:49.602 --> 12:52.855
<i>It enthralls Abraham Lincoln,</i>
<i>who almost on a daily basis</i>

12:52.855 --> 12:54.941
<i>would send Grant</i>
<i>a telegraph asking,</i>

12:54.941 --> 12:58.319
<i>"How's work on the canal</i>
<i>coming along?"</i>

12:58.319 --> 13:01.281
And Grant would send back
these very rosy reports.

13:01.281 --> 13:04.033
<i>But Sherman was</i>
<i>far more candid when he said,</i>

13:04.033 --> 13:06.119
<i>"The canal</i>
<i>don't amount to much."</i>

13:06.119 --> 13:08.496
<i>And by late March,</i>
<i>even Grant would realize</i>

13:08.496 --> 13:11.040
<i>that this canal was a bust.</i>

13:11.040 --> 13:13.626
[rain pattering]

13:13.626 --> 13:15.128
<i>And at this point in time,</i>

13:15.128 --> 13:17.755
<i>it's the rainy season</i>
<i>in Mississippi.</i>

13:17.755 --> 13:19.299
[thunder rumbling]

13:19.299 --> 13:22.927
<i>‐ The whole country</i>
<i>was covered with water.</i>

13:22.927 --> 13:25.388
<i>Troops could scarcely</i>
<i>find dry ground</i>

13:25.388 --> 13:28.016
<i>on which to pitch their tents.</i>

13:28.016 --> 13:30.810
<i>Malarial fevers</i>
<i>broke out among the men.</i>

13:30.810 --> 13:32.645
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:32.645 --> 13:35.940
<i>‐ Vicksburg shows a number</i>
<i>of qualities of Grant.</i>

13:35.940 --> 13:38.693
<i>There's again a degree</i>
<i>of determination.</i>

13:38.693 --> 13:42.488
<i>He tries every which way</i>
<i>to come at Vicksburg,</i>

13:42.488 --> 13:45.783
but on any battlefield
or in any campaign,

13:45.783 --> 13:47.869
results do matter.

13:47.869 --> 13:49.162
<i>♪ ♪</i>

13:49.162 --> 13:50.747
<i>‐ Now, at this point in time,</i>

13:50.747 --> 13:52.498
<i>Lincoln changed his generals</i>

13:52.498 --> 13:54.542
almost as frequently
as he changed his shirts.

13:54.542 --> 13:58.046
<i>So Grant realized that</i>
<i>his time and his options</i>

13:58.046 --> 14:00.256
<i>were running out.</i>

14:00.256 --> 14:04.218
[rain pattering,
thunder rumbling]

14:04.218 --> 14:07.513
[indistinct chatter]

14:07.513 --> 14:14.520
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:19.859 --> 14:21.694
‐ General.

14:21.694 --> 14:28.701
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:33.831 --> 14:36.042
‐ Have you heard?

14:36.042 --> 14:39.587
I'm stuck in the mud
in northern Mississippi.

14:39.587 --> 14:43.716
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:43.716 --> 14:45.718
Vicksburg.

14:45.718 --> 14:48.137
<i>♪ ♪</i>

14:48.137 --> 14:51.265
We need to get out of this mud
and into the water.

14:51.265 --> 14:53.017
‐ What do you mean?

14:53.017 --> 14:55.228
‐ Use the river to advance.

14:55.228 --> 14:58.147
Move our men south.

14:58.147 --> 15:00.274
Ferry them across here.

15:00.274 --> 15:04.695
‐ But we'll need to get ships
south to transport our men.

15:04.695 --> 15:06.739
‐ If we move those ships
past the Vicksburg guns,

15:06.739 --> 15:10.201
they'll blow us
out of the water.

15:10.201 --> 15:11.410
‐ It's too risky.

15:11.410 --> 15:13.329
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:13.329 --> 15:15.790
‐ There's no other way.

15:15.790 --> 15:17.750
It's time to take a risk.

15:17.750 --> 15:19.335
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:19.335 --> 15:22.755
Gentlemen...

15:22.755 --> 15:27.260
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:27.260 --> 15:29.262
I'm gonna run their guns.

15:29.262 --> 15:33.516
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:33.516 --> 15:36.644
<i>‐ This is thought</i>
<i>to be suicidal.</i>

15:36.644 --> 15:39.105
Everybody believes
this is a losing proposition.

15:39.105 --> 15:42.650
<i>♪ ♪</i>

15:42.650 --> 15:45.278
<i>‐ The gunboats</i>
<i>of the Mississippi squadron,</i>

15:45.278 --> 15:47.321
although they are ironclad,

15:47.321 --> 15:49.282
<i>the roofs of these gunboats</i>

15:49.282 --> 15:52.285
<i>are vulnerable</i>
<i>to a plunging fire.</i>

15:52.285 --> 15:54.620
<i>[guns firing]</i>

15:54.620 --> 15:56.664
<i>‐ Sherman cautions him</i>
<i>against it.</i>

15:56.664 --> 15:59.167
<i>Sherman says,</i>
<i>"I want this on paper</i>

15:59.167 --> 16:01.043
<i>that I'm against this."</i>

16:01.043 --> 16:03.129
And Grant can live with that.

16:03.129 --> 16:04.797
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:04.797 --> 16:08.718
<i>‐ Grant had something to prove</i>
<i>during the Civil War.</i>

16:08.718 --> 16:12.471
He must have known that
this was his chance to show

16:12.471 --> 16:14.098
what he had inside him.

16:14.098 --> 16:17.393
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:17.393 --> 16:21.689
<i>‐ The plan is, while the boats</i>
<i>will run the batteries,</i>

16:21.689 --> 16:25.860
<i>Grant will march his men down</i>
<i>the western side of the river.</i>

16:25.860 --> 16:27.612
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:27.612 --> 16:31.032
<i>Ironclads provide protection</i>
<i>for his transports.</i>

16:31.032 --> 16:32.617
<i>The transports are there</i>
<i>because they are</i>

16:32.617 --> 16:34.202
<i>gonna move his troops</i>
<i>from one side</i>

16:34.202 --> 16:36.078
<i>of the river to the other</i>

16:36.078 --> 16:37.705
<i>and then run a land campaign</i>

16:37.705 --> 16:39.707
<i>to come in</i>
<i>from the eastern side.</i>

16:39.707 --> 16:44.045
<i>♪ ♪</i>

16:44.045 --> 16:46.005
<i>‐ In preparation,</i>
<i>all the gunboats</i>

16:46.005 --> 16:47.757
<i>are painted black.</i>

16:47.757 --> 16:51.010
<i>Bales of cotton,</i>
<i>bales of hay are stacked</i>

16:51.010 --> 16:53.721
<i>around the engines</i>
<i>to muffle the sounds,</i>

16:53.721 --> 16:55.306
as well as out
on the gun decks,

16:55.306 --> 16:58.142
to absorb incoming rounds
of Confederate ammunition.

16:58.142 --> 17:01.145
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:01.145 --> 17:03.105
<i>Around 11:00 at night,</i>

17:03.105 --> 17:05.149
<i>the gunboats</i>
<i>and transport vessels,</i>

17:05.149 --> 17:07.693
<i>in single‐file line,</i>
<i>will slowly drift</i>

17:07.693 --> 17:09.695
<i>with the current.</i>

17:09.695 --> 17:15.576
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:15.576 --> 17:17.370
<i>‐</i> Sir, they've set fire
to the opposite shore

17:17.370 --> 17:18.412
so they can see us coming.

17:18.412 --> 17:25.461
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:29.173 --> 17:32.134
[artillery firing]

17:36.055 --> 17:39.392
‐ There they go.

17:39.392 --> 17:42.853
<i>‐ The enemy were evidently</i>
<i>expecting our fleet.</i>

17:42.853 --> 17:45.064
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:45.064 --> 17:48.568
<i>The sight was magnificent...</i>

17:48.568 --> 17:50.528
<i>but terrible.</i>

17:50.528 --> 17:53.656
<i>♪ ♪</i>

17:53.656 --> 17:55.908
<i>‐ Now, on the night</i>
<i>of April the 16th,</i>

17:55.908 --> 17:58.744
<i>Admiral David Porter</i>
<i>pays very close attention</i>

17:58.744 --> 18:02.957
<i>as to where the shot and shell</i>
<i>are hitting his vessels.</i>

18:02.957 --> 18:05.209
<i>They are hitting</i>
<i>his smokestacks,</i>

18:05.209 --> 18:08.588
but almost none are getting any
lower to where the vital parts

18:08.588 --> 18:10.047
of your boats are situated.

18:10.047 --> 18:12.758
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:12.758 --> 18:15.261
<i>And he realizes</i>
<i>the Confederates can't fire</i>

18:15.261 --> 18:20.349
<i>against the near bank</i>
<i>of the Mississippi.</i>

18:20.349 --> 18:25.313
<i>And so Porter orders all his</i>
<i>gunboats to hug the shoreline.</i>

18:25.313 --> 18:28.024
<i>So close did they come</i>
<i>that almost all</i>

18:28.024 --> 18:32.069
<i>the Confederate shots are now</i>
<i>flying harmlessly overhead.</i>

18:32.069 --> 18:37.116
<i>♪ ♪</i>

18:37.116 --> 18:40.578
<i>‐</i> They're getting through,
Rawlins.

18:40.578 --> 18:43.623
They're getting through.

18:43.623 --> 18:45.374
We're gonna take Vicksburg
in a few days.

18:45.374 --> 18:47.627
By God, at last.

18:47.627 --> 18:50.630
‐ We'll end this war now.

18:50.630 --> 18:53.299
‐ I think so too, John.

18:53.299 --> 18:55.551
Let's see where we stand
when the sun comes up.

18:55.551 --> 18:57.970
Get a message
to Admiral Porter,

18:57.970 --> 19:01.807
see what condition the boats
and the men are in.

19:01.807 --> 19:04.352
‐ Sir.

19:04.352 --> 19:07.980
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:07.980 --> 19:10.107
<i>‐ Due to the success</i>
<i>of the passage</i>

19:10.107 --> 19:12.777
<i>on the night</i>
<i>of April the 16th,</i>

19:12.777 --> 19:15.821
Grant would transport
24,000 soldiers

19:15.821 --> 19:18.824
across the mighty river.

19:18.824 --> 19:20.660
<i>‐ I think what we see</i>
<i>in Vicksburg</i>

19:20.660 --> 19:23.704
is the maturity of Grant

19:23.704 --> 19:26.499
and the decisions
that he makes.

19:26.499 --> 19:30.586
<i>It's an extraordinary campaign</i>
<i>at the operational level.</i>

19:30.586 --> 19:33.130
<i>How do armies move</i>
<i>from point to point?</i>

19:33.130 --> 19:35.508
<i>How do they</i>
<i>sustain themselves?</i>

19:35.508 --> 19:38.803
<i>And that's all separate</i>
<i>from battle itself.</i>

19:38.803 --> 19:41.430
<i>‐ Grant's decision</i>
<i>to run those batteries,</i>

19:41.430 --> 19:43.641
<i>the determination,</i>
<i>the grit,</i>

19:43.641 --> 19:46.018
<i>this is utterly part</i>
<i>of his makeup.</i>

19:46.018 --> 19:49.522
And the loss of ships running
Vicksburg batteries is one.

19:49.522 --> 19:52.316
<i>♪ ♪</i>

19:52.316 --> 19:54.151
<i>‐ All the labors,</i>
<i>hardships,</i>

19:54.151 --> 19:56.362
<i>and exposures were</i>
<i>for the accomplishment</i>

19:56.362 --> 19:59.699
<i>of this one object.</i>

19:59.699 --> 20:02.034
<i>I was on dry ground</i>

20:02.034 --> 20:05.079
<i>on the same side</i>
<i>of the river with the enemy.</i>

20:05.079 --> 20:10.209
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:10.209 --> 20:12.002
<i>‐ So he's now run</i>
<i>the batteries,</i>

20:12.002 --> 20:14.046
<i>he's crossed</i>
<i>over the Mississippi River,</i>

20:14.046 --> 20:18.592
<i>and Grant is now</i>
<i>making progress in the west.</i>

20:18.592 --> 20:20.553
<i>♪ ♪</i>

20:20.553 --> 20:22.888
<i>Meanwhile</i>
<i>in the eastern theater,</i>

20:22.888 --> 20:25.683
<i>it's not going well.</i>

20:25.683 --> 20:27.226
<i>‐ At one point,</i>
<i>the Union army</i>

20:27.226 --> 20:29.353
is losing something like
200 men a day

20:29.353 --> 20:31.397
to desertion in early 1863.

20:31.397 --> 20:34.066
So the army is literally
leaving the field.

20:34.066 --> 20:35.568
<i>And then in May of 1863,</i>

20:35.568 --> 20:37.528
<i>you get Lee's greatest victory</i>
<i>of the war</i>

20:37.528 --> 20:39.989
<i>at Chancellorsville.</i>

20:39.989 --> 20:41.741
<i>‐ This is Robert E. Lee's</i>
<i>high point.</i>

20:41.741 --> 20:44.076
Outnumbered two to one,
this is the whole idea

20:44.076 --> 20:46.412
of one Confederate could fight
three Union soldiers.

20:46.412 --> 20:48.456
Here he proves it.

20:48.456 --> 20:49.749
<i>The Union public</i>
<i>is starting to feel like</i>

20:49.749 --> 20:51.751
<i>this is unwinnable.</i>

20:51.751 --> 20:54.587
<i>And so there is</i>
<i>a ticking clock politically,</i>

20:54.587 --> 20:56.422
<i>and everyone</i>
<i>is watching to see</i>

20:56.422 --> 20:58.215
<i>if Grant will be successful.</i>

20:58.215 --> 21:02.762
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:02.762 --> 21:05.389
<i>‐ In May of 1863,</i>

21:05.389 --> 21:09.226
<i>Grant's on that open ground</i>
<i>below Vicksburg.</i>

21:09.226 --> 21:10.603
<i>Now that, mind you,</i>
<i>is only the beginning</i>

21:10.603 --> 21:12.354
<i>of his campaign, though.</i>

21:12.354 --> 21:14.273
'Cause now,
once on the ground,

21:14.273 --> 21:15.816
that's when the campaign really

21:15.816 --> 21:17.109
has to move into high gear.

21:17.109 --> 21:19.445
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:19.445 --> 21:21.781
<i>‐ Once on the Vicksburg side</i>
<i>of the river,</i>

21:21.781 --> 21:23.449
<i>most people would have</i>
<i>expected Grant</i>

21:23.449 --> 21:25.659
<i>to march north</i>
<i>toward Vicksburg.</i>

21:25.659 --> 21:29.288
<i>And yet he doesn't</i>
<i>do anything like that.</i>

21:29.288 --> 21:30.956
First of all,
you don't attack

21:30.956 --> 21:32.666
where the enemy
expects you to attack,

21:32.666 --> 21:34.126
from the south.

21:34.126 --> 21:35.795
<i>Second of all,</i>
<i>in command</i>

21:35.795 --> 21:37.713
<i>of the roughly 30,000</i>
<i>troops of Vicksburg</i>

21:37.713 --> 21:40.466
<i>is John C. Pemberton.</i>

21:40.466 --> 21:43.636
<i>And Pemberton's fortifications</i>
<i>are wildly strong.</i>

21:43.636 --> 21:47.056
<i>♪ ♪</i>

21:47.056 --> 21:50.059
<i>‐ Rather than take</i>
<i>the direct road to Vicksburg,</i>

21:50.059 --> 21:53.813
<i>Grant opts to move</i>
<i>in a northeasterly direction,</i>

21:53.813 --> 21:57.274
<i>cut Pemberton's line</i>
<i>of supply and communication,</i>

21:57.274 --> 22:00.110
<i>isolate his opponent</i>
<i>in Vicksburg,</i>

22:00.110 --> 22:02.780
and then move in for the kill.

22:02.780 --> 22:07.034
<i>Over the next 17 days,</i>
<i>Grant's army will push deep</i>

22:07.034 --> 22:11.497
<i>into the interior</i>
<i>of the state of Mississippi.</i>

22:11.497 --> 22:13.999
<i>‐ However, in the state</i>
<i>capital of Jackson,</i>

22:13.999 --> 22:17.127
<i>another Confederate force</i>
<i>was beginning to organize</i>

22:17.127 --> 22:19.839
<i>under the command</i>
<i>of Joseph Johnston.</i>

22:19.839 --> 22:23.843
So Grant was really facing two
separate Confederate armies

22:23.843 --> 22:25.594
deep in enemy territory

22:25.594 --> 22:29.306
with a extraordinarily
limited supply line.

22:29.306 --> 22:32.935
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:32.935 --> 22:35.354
<i>‐ There is actually</i>
<i>great risk for that moment.</i>

22:35.354 --> 22:37.314
He turns his back
on Pemberton's army,

22:37.314 --> 22:39.191
nearly the same size
of his own.

22:39.191 --> 22:41.902
<i>♪ ♪</i>

22:41.902 --> 22:43.529
<i>A commander always</i>
<i>needs to know himself,</i>

22:43.529 --> 22:46.365
<i>know the environment,</i>
<i>know the enemy.</i>

22:46.365 --> 22:48.367
<i>He knows John Pemberton.</i>

22:48.367 --> 22:50.327
<i>He knows he's not aggressive,</i>

22:50.327 --> 22:51.745
<i>and he thinks,</i>

22:51.745 --> 22:53.372
<i>"If I strike quickly,</i>
<i>I can defeat them</i>

22:53.372 --> 22:55.165
<i>"in piecemeal</i>
<i>before they join,</i>

22:55.165 --> 22:56.417
<i>"and therefore,</i>
<i>it's an advantage</i>

22:56.417 --> 22:58.460
<i>to have</i>
<i>this central position."</i>

22:58.460 --> 22:59.879
And that's exactly
what he does.

22:59.879 --> 23:03.048
He accepts risk by leaving
Pemberton in his rear,

23:03.048 --> 23:05.259
and he's gonna go ahead
and turn and attack Jackson.

23:05.259 --> 23:09.555
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:09.555 --> 23:11.557
<i>‐ And on May the 14th,</i>

23:11.557 --> 23:13.767
<i>Grant's armies</i>
<i>will drive Confederate forces</i>

23:13.767 --> 23:15.394
<i>out of Jackson</i>

23:15.394 --> 23:19.440
<i>and destroy Pemberton's line</i>
<i>of supply and communication.</i>

23:19.440 --> 23:22.735
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:22.735 --> 23:25.362
<i>With Johnston's forces</i>
<i>scattered to the winds,</i>

23:25.362 --> 23:27.615
<i>Grant will turn west</i>
<i>toward Vicksburg.</i>

23:27.615 --> 23:29.533
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:29.533 --> 23:30.910
<i>‐ Pemberton all of a sudden</i>

23:30.910 --> 23:32.745
realizes Grant
has turned west.

23:32.745 --> 23:34.747
<i>And this is when</i>
<i>Pemberton decides,</i>

23:34.747 --> 23:37.917
<i>"I gotta stop</i>
<i>and give battle."</i>

23:37.917 --> 23:40.210
<i>The numbers are largely equal,</i>

23:40.210 --> 23:43.297
<i>somewhere less than</i>
<i>30,000 on each side.</i>

23:43.297 --> 23:44.798
<i>♪ ♪</i>

23:44.798 --> 23:49.303
<i>‐</i> If Ulysses S. Grant
loses a stand‐up fight,

23:49.303 --> 23:52.556
<i>his army is in trouble.</i>

23:52.556 --> 23:56.352
<i>They have cast off</i>
<i>most of their logistics.</i>

23:56.352 --> 23:58.896
They are
in Confederate territory.

23:58.896 --> 24:03.567
<i>But if there is a way he can</i>
<i>beat the Confederate army</i>

24:03.567 --> 24:06.570
<i>without having</i>
<i>to storm Vicksburg,</i>

24:06.570 --> 24:09.782
<i>he is more than willing</i>
<i>to do it.</i>

24:09.782 --> 24:12.660
<i>♪ ♪</i>

24:12.660 --> 24:15.037
<i>‐ Champion Hill,</i>
<i>where Pemberton had chosen</i>

24:15.037 --> 24:16.580
<i>to receive us,</i>

24:16.580 --> 24:19.458
<i>was well selected.</i>

24:19.458 --> 24:21.627
<i>It is one</i>
<i>of the highest points</i>

24:21.627 --> 24:25.047
<i>and commanded all the ground.</i>

24:25.047 --> 24:29.385
[militaristic drum and fife
music playing]

24:29.385 --> 24:34.348
♪ ♪

24:34.348 --> 24:38.644
Tell General McClernand to have
his men advance quickly.

24:38.644 --> 24:40.437
Osterhaus and Carr
to push the center.

24:40.437 --> 24:43.273
Blair and Smith should advance
quickly on the left.

24:43.273 --> 24:46.986
[artillery firing]

24:46.986 --> 24:49.989
♪ ♪

24:49.989 --> 24:52.157
<i>‐ Grant could feel</i>
<i>a battlefield.</i>

24:52.157 --> 24:55.327
<i>He could see it in his mind,</i>

24:55.327 --> 24:56.954
not just in space,
because keep in mind

24:56.954 --> 24:59.623
it's not just
who's on the left, the right,

24:59.623 --> 25:03.085
the center,
but in time...

25:03.085 --> 25:06.964
<i>because it's sequencing</i>
<i>the different activities.</i>

25:06.964 --> 25:09.633
<i>And that is really</i>
<i>just short of genius.</i>

25:09.633 --> 25:14.179
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:14.179 --> 25:17.182
<i>‐</i> I see a break
in Pemberton's line.

25:17.182 --> 25:18.642
Tell McPherson
to flank to the left

25:18.642 --> 25:21.145
and press them hard.

25:21.145 --> 25:24.148
[soldiers clamoring]

25:24.148 --> 25:27.151
[artillery firing]

25:27.151 --> 25:34.116
<i>♪ ♪</i>

25:55.846 --> 25:57.723
‐ The rebs are running, sir.

25:57.723 --> 26:00.392
‐ Hell, they're running
all the way to Vicksburg.

26:00.392 --> 26:03.645
‐ Send General Osterhaus
to follow them.

26:03.645 --> 26:05.397
I want to thin them out
before we face them again

26:05.397 --> 26:07.399
at Vicksburg.

26:07.399 --> 26:13.572
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:13.572 --> 26:16.200
<i>‐ An army on the move</i>
<i>is an army to be destroyed.</i>

26:16.200 --> 26:17.701
<i>And therefore,</i>
<i>he's gonna continue</i>

26:17.701 --> 26:19.912
<i>to push Pemberton's army.</i>

26:19.912 --> 26:21.663
<i>And this is gonna drive</i>
<i>the Confederates back</i>

26:21.663 --> 26:24.416
into the defenses
of Vicksburg.

26:24.416 --> 26:27.544
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:27.544 --> 26:30.172
<i>‐ Grant took enormous risk</i>
<i>when he went east</i>

26:30.172 --> 26:33.425
<i>rather than immediately</i>
<i>to Vicksburg.</i>

26:33.425 --> 26:37.721
But he very deftly
defeats piecemeal

26:37.721 --> 26:39.932
the different
Confederate forces

26:39.932 --> 26:43.227
that are trying to come
to reinforce Vicksburg,

26:43.227 --> 26:46.563
<i>and essentially, it's a siege</i>
<i>from there on out.</i>

26:46.563 --> 26:48.607
[indistinct chatter]

26:48.607 --> 26:51.443
<i>‐ As long as we could hold</i>
<i>our position,</i>

26:51.443 --> 26:54.279
<i>the enemy was limited</i>
<i>in supplies of food,</i>

26:54.279 --> 26:56.990
<i>men, and ammunition.</i>

26:56.990 --> 26:59.827
<i>♪ ♪</i>

26:59.827 --> 27:02.496
[gunshot]

27:04.581 --> 27:10.796
<i>♪ ♪</i>
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:17.136 --> 27:19.221
<i>‐</i> Keep these men digging,
Captain.

27:19.221 --> 27:21.640
Let's be done with this
by nightfall.

27:21.640 --> 27:24.476
‐ Yes, sir.

27:24.476 --> 27:26.019
<i>‐ Ulysses S. Grant has now</i>

27:26.019 --> 27:27.271
gone down
the Mississippi River.

27:27.271 --> 27:30.858
He's in the midst
of the Vicksburg Campaign.

27:30.858 --> 27:33.402
<i>In 17 days,</i>
<i>Grant's army marched</i>

27:33.402 --> 27:36.613
<i>200 miles</i>
<i>and won five battles.</i>

27:36.613 --> 27:39.616
<i>And now we are talking</i>
<i>about a siege.</i>

27:39.616 --> 27:42.327
<i>♪ ♪</i>

27:42.327 --> 27:45.038
<i>‐ When Grant first settles</i>
<i>into siege operations,</i>

27:45.038 --> 27:47.749
<i>he digs a line opposite</i>
<i>the Confederate ones,</i>

27:47.749 --> 27:52.629
<i>so you can cut off the key</i>
<i>routes of supply to the city.</i>

27:52.629 --> 27:54.089
And then in case
a Confederate force

27:54.089 --> 27:56.383
came from his rear,
he then dug another

27:56.383 --> 27:58.802
series of entrenchments
facing the other way.

27:58.802 --> 28:00.429
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:00.429 --> 28:03.682
<i>And now he's gonna ring</i>
<i>Vicksburg with artillery.</i>

28:03.682 --> 28:05.517
<i>In fact,</i>
<i>he's even gonna bring</i>

28:05.517 --> 28:07.477
<i>naval artillery</i>
<i>off naval ships</i>

28:07.477 --> 28:09.062
<i>to bombard Vicksburg.</i>

28:09.062 --> 28:11.481
<i>We want to put them</i>
<i>under the maximum pressure</i>

28:11.481 --> 28:13.233
<i>so that they recognize</i>
<i>this sacrifice</i>

28:13.233 --> 28:15.903
<i>is no longer worth it.</i>

28:15.903 --> 28:18.697
‐ And Grant ordered
his soldiers to begin sinking

28:18.697 --> 28:21.950
approaches toward
the Confederate works.

28:21.950 --> 28:23.952
<i>And so you have</i>
<i>Union engineers,</i>

28:23.952 --> 28:25.454
<i>and they'd be working</i>
<i>behind the protection</i>

28:25.454 --> 28:28.123
<i>of what was called</i>
<i>a sap roller,</i>

28:28.123 --> 28:30.792
<i>normally a bundle</i>
<i>of cane and vine</i>

28:30.792 --> 28:32.586
<i>packed with dirt or cotton,</i>

28:32.586 --> 28:34.421
<i>anything that'll stop</i>
<i>a bullet.</i>

28:34.421 --> 28:36.798
<i>And the whole object</i>
<i>is to get all the way</i>

28:36.798 --> 28:39.092
<i>up to the Confederate line.</i>

28:39.092 --> 28:43.055
<i>♪ ♪</i>

28:46.099 --> 28:48.018
[gunfire]

28:48.018 --> 28:49.770
‐ Sharpshooters!
Get down!

28:49.770 --> 28:50.938
Sharpshooters!

28:50.938 --> 28:52.356
‐ Sharpshooters!

28:52.356 --> 28:54.441
‐ Get down!
Get down!

28:54.441 --> 28:55.901
‐ See them?

28:55.901 --> 28:57.903
Where are they?
[gunfire]

28:57.903 --> 29:00.656
‐ Get down!
Everybody get down!

29:00.656 --> 29:01.865
‐ We gotta move!

29:01.865 --> 29:08.830
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:18.757 --> 29:21.468
[gunshot]

29:21.468 --> 29:23.595
‐ Cease fire!

29:23.595 --> 29:25.639
Hold your fire!

29:25.639 --> 29:26.765
‐ Hold fire!

29:26.765 --> 29:27.849
‐ They're gone!

29:27.849 --> 29:29.726
‐ Hold fire!

29:29.726 --> 29:35.899
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:35.899 --> 29:37.901
‐ I'll take that.

29:37.901 --> 29:40.320
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:40.320 --> 29:42.364
All right, everyone!

29:42.364 --> 29:44.366
All right, get back to work!

29:44.366 --> 29:45.617
Now!

29:45.617 --> 29:47.619
Get back to work!

29:47.619 --> 29:49.871
<i>♪ ♪</i>

29:49.871 --> 29:52.916
<i>‐ When it has been made clear</i>
<i>that the Negro,</i>

29:52.916 --> 29:54.751
<i>as an independent laborer,</i>

29:54.751 --> 29:57.170
<i>can do these things well,</i>

29:57.170 --> 30:00.257
<i>it would be very easy</i>
<i>to put a musket in his hands</i>

30:00.257 --> 30:02.092
<i>and make a soldier of him.</i>

30:02.092 --> 30:06.096
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:06.096 --> 30:08.974
<i>‐ Throughout the Civil War,</i>
<i>African‐Americans</i>

30:08.974 --> 30:12.644
<i>start to flee</i>
<i>to Union army encampments</i>

30:12.644 --> 30:16.857
in hopes of finding
some mechanism for freedom.

30:16.857 --> 30:18.400
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:18.400 --> 30:21.111
<i>Essentially, what these</i>
<i>African‐Americans do</i>

30:21.111 --> 30:23.655
<i>is, they appeal</i>
<i>to the Union army and say,</i>

30:23.655 --> 30:26.825
<i>"Make use of me</i>
<i>in this conflict."</i>

30:26.825 --> 30:31.288
<i>‐</i> If the logic of war
is any resources,

30:31.288 --> 30:35.208
whether it be guns, you know,
cannon, fortifications,

30:35.208 --> 30:38.503
if the enemy is using something
to support their war effort,

30:38.503 --> 30:41.381
it can be legitimately
taken away.

30:41.381 --> 30:43.884
<i>So by the end of the first</i>
<i>year of the war,</i>

30:43.884 --> 30:45.677
<i>Lincoln has come</i>
<i>to the conclusion</i>

30:45.677 --> 30:49.347
<i>that emancipation</i>
<i>is a necessary war angle.</i>

30:49.347 --> 30:51.433
<i>♪ ♪</i>

30:51.433 --> 30:53.769
<i>‐ In Grant's own</i>
<i>personal life,</i>

30:53.769 --> 30:56.104
the fact that he married
into a family

30:56.104 --> 30:59.858
that was dependent
on the system of slavery...

30:59.858 --> 31:04.362
<i>his decision to grant</i>
<i>freedom to a slave...</i>

31:04.362 --> 31:08.241
<i>the fact that during</i>
<i>his time in Missouri,</i>

31:08.241 --> 31:11.244
<i>he's tilling the soil</i>
<i>with enslaved people,</i>

31:11.244 --> 31:13.580
<i>I think illustrates how</i>

31:13.580 --> 31:15.707
<i>Grant's life is actually</i>
<i>an object lesson</i>

31:15.707 --> 31:19.127
<i>in the ways that a person</i>
<i>has to grapple</i>

31:19.127 --> 31:22.422
<i>with their position</i>
<i>on equality.</i>

31:22.422 --> 31:25.467
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:25.467 --> 31:30.055
<i>‐ And then Lincoln issues</i>
<i>the Emancipation Proclamation.</i>

31:30.055 --> 31:34.601
This goes into effect
as both civil and military law

31:34.601 --> 31:38.730
on the 1st of January, 1863.

31:38.730 --> 31:41.733
<i>‐ When Lincoln put out</i>
<i>the Emancipation Proclamation,</i>

31:41.733 --> 31:44.903
it was an amazing thing.

31:44.903 --> 31:48.240
One out of every four
enslaved African‐Americans

31:48.240 --> 31:50.242
<i>made their way to freedom.</i>

31:50.242 --> 31:52.702
<i>♪ ♪</i>

31:52.702 --> 31:54.121
<i>‐ The most important part</i>

31:54.121 --> 31:55.372
<i>of the Emancipation</i>
<i>Proclamation</i>

31:55.372 --> 31:57.874
is, that's the moment
where Lincoln first,

31:57.874 --> 32:00.919
you know, calls up black people
to fight in the armies

32:00.919 --> 32:01.920
of the country.

32:01.920 --> 32:03.922
That is significant.

32:03.922 --> 32:05.549
<i>That is actually a huge,</i>
<i>huge deal</i>

32:05.549 --> 32:08.927
<i>and has, you know, great</i>
<i>implications on the North</i>

32:08.927 --> 32:11.805
<i>actually winning the war.</i>

32:11.805 --> 32:13.849
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:13.849 --> 32:16.434
<i>‐ And so beginning in 1863,</i>

32:16.434 --> 32:19.437
<i>you have your first appearance</i>

32:19.437 --> 32:22.899
<i>of black soldiers</i>
<i>in blue uniforms.</i>

32:22.899 --> 32:24.693
<i>Their first engagement,</i>
<i>in fact,</i>

32:24.693 --> 32:27.320
occurs during
the Vicksburg campaign.

32:27.320 --> 32:30.907
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:30.907 --> 32:32.868
<i>‐ During the course</i>
<i>of the siege of Vicksburg,</i>

32:32.868 --> 32:35.036
<i>Grant had established</i>
<i>supply enclaves</i>

32:35.036 --> 32:37.664
<i>at places such</i>
<i>as Milliken's Bend.</i>

32:37.664 --> 32:40.000
<i>And most of these</i>
<i>supply enclaves</i>

32:40.000 --> 32:43.295
were defended by recently
recruited black troops

32:43.295 --> 32:44.629
in Union blue.

32:44.629 --> 32:46.214
<i>♪ ♪</i>

32:46.214 --> 32:48.842
<i>But at the same time,</i>
<i>Confederates west of Vicksburg</i>

32:48.842 --> 32:50.760
<i>were ordered to do</i>

32:50.760 --> 32:54.723
<i>"something on behalf</i>
<i>of the garrison of Vicksburg."</i>

32:54.723 --> 32:57.642
<i>And so on June the 7th,</i>
<i>a Confederate brigade</i>

32:57.642 --> 33:02.147
<i>would attack the supply</i>
<i>enclave at Milliken's Bend.</i>

33:02.147 --> 33:04.858
‐ And it is at this moment
that two things

33:04.858 --> 33:06.234
become very clear:

33:06.234 --> 33:07.986
<i>that they have not been given</i>

33:07.986 --> 33:09.613
<i>the best training,</i>

33:09.613 --> 33:11.406
<i>nor have they been given</i>
<i>the best weaponry</i>

33:11.406 --> 33:14.910
<i>to protect themselves.</i>

33:14.910 --> 33:16.328
<i>‐</i> The thing to recognize
about the colored troops

33:16.328 --> 33:19.539
is, expectations were so low.

33:19.539 --> 33:22.000
<i>I mean, the idea</i>
<i>that black people</i>

33:22.000 --> 33:24.085
<i>would fight as soldiers...</i>

33:24.085 --> 33:28.006
<i>I mean, this was like</i>
<i>a man going to the moon.</i>

33:28.006 --> 33:31.009
[soldiers clamoring]

33:31.009 --> 33:38.016
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:02.082 --> 34:04.876
‐ [roaring]

34:04.876 --> 34:11.883
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:13.218 --> 34:16.012
<i>‐ This was the first important</i>
<i>engagement of the war</i>

34:16.012 --> 34:19.516
<i>in which colored troops</i>
<i>were under fire.</i>

34:19.516 --> 34:21.559
<i>These men were very raw,</i>

34:21.559 --> 34:25.230
<i>having all been enlisted since</i>
<i>the beginning of the siege,</i>

34:25.230 --> 34:28.108
<i>but they were most gallant,</i>
<i>and I doubt not</i>

34:28.108 --> 34:30.902
<i>they will make good troops.</i>

34:30.902 --> 34:33.113
<i>‐</i> There were 1,500
Confederates pitted against

34:33.113 --> 34:36.574
a little more than
1,000 Union troops.

34:36.574 --> 34:38.076
<i>The Confederates</i>
<i>would drive them back</i>

34:38.076 --> 34:39.577
<i>from their fortifications,</i>

34:39.577 --> 34:41.246
<i>through their encampment,</i>

34:41.246 --> 34:45.125
<i>and all the way</i>
<i>to the Mississippi River.</i>

34:45.125 --> 34:48.753
Black soldiers would lose
70% of their numbers,

34:48.753 --> 34:51.965
but they would successfully
hold on to the supply enclave

34:51.965 --> 34:53.258
at Milliken's Bend.

34:53.258 --> 34:55.719
<i>♪ ♪</i>

34:55.719 --> 34:58.972
<i>‐ Lincoln says he can</i>
<i>no longer consider an idea</i>

34:58.972 --> 35:01.766
of going back to things
being the way they were

35:01.766 --> 35:04.477
after black people have
actually died for the country.

35:04.477 --> 35:06.479
You can't restore those people
to slavery again.

35:06.479 --> 35:08.106
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:08.106 --> 35:12.068
<i>‐ And in fact,</i>
<i>by the end of the Civil War,</i>

35:12.068 --> 35:15.030
almost 200,000
African‐Americans,

35:15.030 --> 35:18.283
you know,
fight on the Union side.

35:18.283 --> 35:20.910
<i>‐ To His Excellency</i>
<i>A. Lincoln:</i>

35:20.910 --> 35:25.665
<i>Sir, by arming the Negro,</i>
<i>we have added a powerful ally.</i>

35:25.665 --> 35:28.501
<i>This, with the emancipation</i>
<i>of the Negro,</i>

35:28.501 --> 35:32.005
<i>is the heaviest blow</i>
<i>yet given the Confederacy.</i>

35:34.132 --> 35:35.800
[indistinct chatter]

35:35.800 --> 35:37.969
[gunfire]

35:37.969 --> 35:44.934
<i>♪ ♪</i>

35:50.523 --> 35:53.526
<i>‐ The primary strategy</i>
<i>of any siege</i>

35:53.526 --> 35:58.281
<i>is isolating the people</i>
<i>you are besieging inside,</i>

35:58.281 --> 36:01.660
causing them to use up
both their military resources

36:01.660 --> 36:04.329
but especially their food

36:04.329 --> 36:07.999
<i>to force them to capitulate.</i>

36:07.999 --> 36:10.877
<i>So the consequence of this</i>
<i>is, Grant's army will grow</i>

36:10.877 --> 36:15.340
<i>to over 70,000 troops</i>
<i>over time...</i>

36:15.340 --> 36:17.926
and it's a ratcheting up
of military pressure.

36:17.926 --> 36:20.512
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:20.512 --> 36:23.390
<i>‐ Now, the Confederate</i>
<i>government in Richmond</i>

36:23.390 --> 36:27.894
<i>is rather concerned about</i>
<i>the situation at Vicksburg.</i>

36:27.894 --> 36:31.022
<i>And there has emerged</i>
<i>a group that believes</i>

36:31.022 --> 36:33.191
that less focus needs
to be placed on the east,

36:33.191 --> 36:34.818
where things are going well,

36:34.818 --> 36:36.903
and more focus needs
to be put on the west,

36:36.903 --> 36:38.446
where things
are not going well.

36:38.446 --> 36:39.906
<i>♪ ♪</i>

36:39.906 --> 36:42.367
<i>Robert E. Lee's response is,</i>

36:42.367 --> 36:44.369
<i>"Even if I send troops</i>
<i>to Vicksburg,</i>

36:44.369 --> 36:46.705
<i>"by the time they got there,</i>

36:46.705 --> 36:48.373
<i>it might be over."</i>

36:48.373 --> 36:51.251
<i>And Lee decides to go north</i>

36:51.251 --> 36:53.378
<i>and try to seek</i>
<i>a decisive engagement</i>

36:53.378 --> 36:57.424
<i>with the federals</i>
<i>north of Pennsylvania.</i>

36:57.424 --> 37:00.051
<i>[gunshot]</i>

37:00.051 --> 37:02.554
<i>At the same time,</i>
<i>Grant keeps the pressure up</i>

37:02.554 --> 37:05.390
<i>at Vicksburg to end the siege.</i>

37:05.390 --> 37:07.475
<i>[gunshot]</i>

37:07.475 --> 37:08.727
<i>‐ By the end of June,</i>

37:08.727 --> 37:10.478
<i>the Confederate Army</i>
<i>of Vicksburg</i>

37:10.478 --> 37:13.273
was subsisting
on a handful of peas and rice

37:13.273 --> 37:16.067
issued once a day per man.

37:16.067 --> 37:17.610
<i>Even their water</i>
<i>would be rationed</i>

37:17.610 --> 37:20.572
<i>to one cup per man</i>
<i>per day.</i>

37:20.572 --> 37:22.782
<i>♪ ♪</i>

37:22.782 --> 37:24.284
‐ So now as the temperature
of the summer

37:24.284 --> 37:26.244
continues to get
hotter and hotter,

37:26.244 --> 37:27.704
<i>Grant will dam up</i>

37:27.704 --> 37:29.497
<i>all the creeks</i>
<i>that are going in there.</i>

37:29.497 --> 37:30.957
<i>[cannon booms]</i>

37:30.957 --> 37:33.960
<i>Confederates are being shelled</i>
<i>by Union gunboats</i>

37:33.960 --> 37:36.671
<i>as well as Union batteries.</i>

37:36.671 --> 37:40.258
<i>[cannon booms]</i>

37:40.258 --> 37:42.594
<i>‐ But also,</i>
<i>throughout the siege,</i>

37:42.594 --> 37:46.598
<i>you have a civilian population</i>
<i>trapped in the city,</i>

37:46.598 --> 37:49.809
<i>estimated at about 2,000.</i>

37:49.809 --> 37:52.353
<i>And the citizens</i>
<i>lived underground</i>

37:52.353 --> 37:56.149
<i>in man‐made caves to escape</i>
<i>the constant bombardment</i>

37:56.149 --> 37:59.277
<i>of Union cannon</i>
<i>and heavy mortar.</i>

37:59.277 --> 38:01.946
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:01.946 --> 38:04.866
<i>And about the only time</i>
<i>they came out of these caves</i>

38:04.866 --> 38:06.785
<i>is when the Union</i>
<i>artillerymen</i>

38:06.785 --> 38:09.954
<i>ate their morning, noon,</i>
<i>and evening meals.</i>

38:09.954 --> 38:11.414
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:11.414 --> 38:13.625
‐ Grant knows full well

38:13.625 --> 38:17.629
the suffering of the civilians
in Vicksburg.

38:17.629 --> 38:19.798
<i>He doesn't relish any of it,</i>

38:19.798 --> 38:22.884
<i>but I think he does believe</i>

38:22.884 --> 38:26.471
<i>without breaking the will</i>
<i>of the Southern people</i>

38:26.471 --> 38:29.974
<i>that this war is not</i>
<i>gonna come to an end.</i>

38:29.974 --> 38:31.184
<i>‐</i> These civilians
at Vicksburg,

38:31.184 --> 38:32.811
who weeks earlier
were able to get

38:32.811 --> 38:35.980
all the food they needed,
were clearly starving.

38:35.980 --> 38:38.650
<i>And they started eating</i>
<i>anything that moved,</i>

38:38.650 --> 38:40.485
<i>rats included.</i>

38:40.485 --> 38:42.695
<i>And by early July,</i>
<i>it was clear</i>

38:42.695 --> 38:45.740
<i>that the Confederates were</i>
<i>near the end of their rope.</i>

38:45.740 --> 38:50.662
<i>♪ ♪</i>

38:50.662 --> 38:53.540
<i>‐ On July 3rd,</i>
<i>two persons were seen</i>

38:53.540 --> 38:57.377
<i>coming towards our lines</i>
<i>bearing a white flag.</i>

38:57.377 --> 39:00.421
<i>It was a glorious sight</i>
<i>to soldiers on the line.</i>

39:00.421 --> 39:04.217
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:04.217 --> 39:06.719
<i>‐ On the hot afternoon</i>
<i>of July 3rd,</i>

39:06.719 --> 39:08.847
at the very same time
Pickett's legions

39:08.847 --> 39:13.017
were storming over
the stone wall at Gettysburg,

39:13.017 --> 39:15.520
<i>the Confederate commander</i>
<i>John Pemberton</i>

39:15.520 --> 39:17.438
<i>would ask Grant on what terms</i>

39:17.438 --> 39:20.441
<i>he would receive</i>
<i>the surrender of the city.</i>

39:20.441 --> 39:23.653
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:26.030 --> 39:27.365
‐ General Pemberton.

39:27.365 --> 39:34.455
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:34.914 --> 39:36.583
‐ Your terms, General?

39:36.583 --> 39:37.625
Surprise me.

39:37.625 --> 39:39.752
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:39.752 --> 39:43.381
I propose‐‐
‐ No proposals.

39:43.381 --> 39:45.383
Terms won't change.

39:45.383 --> 39:47.802
Unconditional surrender.

39:47.802 --> 39:53.433
<i>♪ ♪</i>

39:53.433 --> 39:55.560
‐ Sir.

39:55.560 --> 39:58.438
Listen, we need to offer terms.

39:58.438 --> 39:59.564
‐ No.

39:59.564 --> 40:00.773
‐ Be practical.

40:00.773 --> 40:03.568
What are we gonna do
with 30,000 prisoners?

40:03.568 --> 40:05.570
Better offer terms,
don't you think?

40:05.570 --> 40:07.822
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:07.822 --> 40:09.157
General.

40:09.157 --> 40:12.744
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:12.744 --> 40:14.954
‐ I'm prepared
to accept the parole

40:14.954 --> 40:16.289
but only if my men walk away

40:16.289 --> 40:18.583
with all of their
personal property.

40:18.583 --> 40:20.919
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:20.919 --> 40:24.255
‐ By personal property,
do you mean to include slaves?

40:24.255 --> 40:27.800
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:27.800 --> 40:30.595
Sidearms, horses...

40:30.595 --> 40:33.264
no slaves.

40:33.264 --> 40:34.933
No slaves leave with you.

40:34.933 --> 40:37.769
<i>♪ ♪</i>

40:37.769 --> 40:41.814
You have until 10:00 tonight.

40:41.814 --> 40:43.775
Then we attack the city.

40:43.775 --> 40:50.823
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:04.629 --> 41:07.632
[indistinct chatter]

41:07.632 --> 41:14.681
<i>♪ ♪</i>

41:19.811 --> 41:21.896
<i>‐ Up to this point,</i>
<i>Grant's reputation</i>

41:21.896 --> 41:24.524
<i>is "Unconditional</i>
<i>Surrender" Grant.</i>

41:24.524 --> 41:27.610
<i>And yet here, he paroles</i>
<i>the men that are there,</i>

41:27.610 --> 41:31.197
<i>and it shows what</i>
<i>flexibility of mind he had.</i>

41:31.197 --> 41:32.907
<i>I think he makes the calculus</i>

41:32.907 --> 41:34.993
of, "What if we send
these 30,000 scarecrows

41:34.993 --> 41:36.953
"back to their towns?

41:36.953 --> 41:38.705
"What are they gonna
tell them?

41:38.705 --> 41:39.998
We just got whipped."

41:39.998 --> 41:42.875
[indistinct chatter]

41:42.875 --> 41:45.753
‐ See the corporal.
He'll sign your parole card.

41:45.753 --> 41:52.760
<i>♪ ♪</i>

42:12.280 --> 42:14.782
‐ General Grant.

42:14.782 --> 42:16.617
‐ Retain your sidearms,
General.

42:16.617 --> 42:23.624
<i>♪ ♪</i>

42:29.130 --> 42:31.883
<i>The enemy</i>
<i>had been suffering,</i>

42:31.883 --> 42:34.761
<i>particularly towards the last.</i>

42:34.761 --> 42:38.598
<i>I saw our men taking bread</i>
<i>from their haversacks</i>

42:38.598 --> 42:41.726
<i>and giving it to the enemy</i>
<i>they had so recently</i>

42:41.726 --> 42:44.729
<i>been engaged in starving out.</i>

42:44.729 --> 42:50.068
<i>♪ ♪</i>

42:50.068 --> 42:53.404
<i>‐ Grant doesn't have</i>
<i>a hatred of Southern people.</i>

42:53.404 --> 42:57.408
He sees them as Americans
that have gone astray.

42:57.408 --> 42:58.993
<i>He doesn't agree</i>
<i>with their cause,</i>

42:58.993 --> 43:01.496
<i>but he cares</i>
<i>for the people themselves.</i>

43:01.496 --> 43:05.750
<i>That really colors the way</i>
<i>he deals with the Confederates</i>

43:05.750 --> 43:08.920
<i>throughout the Civil War.</i>

43:08.920 --> 43:12.090
<i>‐ Vicksburg surrenders,</i>
<i>and the Mississippi is open.</i>

43:12.090 --> 43:13.591
And as Lincoln says,

43:13.591 --> 43:19.764
"The father of waters flows
again, unvexed, to the sea."

43:19.764 --> 43:21.182
<i>♪ ♪</i>

43:21.182 --> 43:23.976
<i>And the great thing is</i>
<i>that the news comes to him</i>

43:23.976 --> 43:27.605
<i>the same weekend as the news</i>
<i>of the victory at Gettysburg.</i>

43:27.605 --> 43:29.607
<i>♪ ♪</i>

43:29.607 --> 43:33.194
<i>‐ My dear General,</i>
<i>when you first reached</i>

43:33.194 --> 43:36.948
<i>the vicinity of Vicksburg,</i>
<i>I never had any faith,</i>

43:36.948 --> 43:42.036
<i>except a general hope that</i>
<i>the expedition could succeed.</i>

43:42.036 --> 43:44.831
<i>I now wish to make</i>
<i>the personal acknowledgment</i>

43:44.831 --> 43:47.708
<i>that you were right</i>
<i>and I was wrong.</i>

43:47.708 --> 43:51.129
<i>Yours very truly,</i>
<i>A. Lincoln.</i>

43:51.129 --> 43:53.297
<i>♪ ♪</i>

43:53.297 --> 43:57.635
<i>‐ Grant and Lincoln</i>
<i>first meet as correspondents.</i>

43:57.635 --> 44:00.179
<i>And their correspondence</i>
<i>is quite wonderful.</i>

44:00.179 --> 44:02.807
<i>They are both men of the west,</i>

44:02.807 --> 44:06.310
<i>and I think they share</i>
<i>a certain philosophy</i>

44:06.310 --> 44:09.147
<i>and perhaps</i>
<i>a certain attitude.</i>

44:09.147 --> 44:10.982
<i>And I think it really</i>
<i>set the terms</i>

44:10.982 --> 44:12.984
<i>for their future relationship.</i>

44:12.984 --> 44:15.153
<i>♪ ♪</i>

44:15.153 --> 44:19.490
This victory was a culmination
of a very long campaign

44:19.490 --> 44:21.075
full of trial and error,

44:21.075 --> 44:25.037
full of Grant figuring out,
"How do I capture

44:25.037 --> 44:27.498
<i>what seemed</i>
<i>an impregnable fort?"</i>

44:27.498 --> 44:34.505
<i>♪ ♪</i>

44:34.505 --> 44:36.841
<i>‐ The Vicksburg campaign</i>
<i>has been studied</i>

44:36.841 --> 44:41.345
<i>by military professionals</i>
<i>ever since July of 1863.</i>

44:41.345 --> 44:43.014
<i>♪ ♪</i>

44:43.014 --> 44:46.184
<i>In fact, in the army's</i>
<i>war‐fighting manual,</i>

44:46.184 --> 44:48.186
<i>it highlights</i>
<i>the Vicksburg campaign</i>

44:48.186 --> 44:49.729
<i>as the most brilliant campaign</i>

44:49.729 --> 44:53.900
<i>ever waged on American soil.</i>

44:53.900 --> 44:55.735
<i>And so whereas</i>
<i>the Civil War is often</i>

44:55.735 --> 44:57.987
referred to as the last
of the old wars,

44:57.987 --> 44:59.697
first of the modern wars,

44:59.697 --> 45:04.952
Grant can be termed the first
modern American warrior.

45:04.952 --> 45:07.622
<i>♪ ♪</i>

45:09.040 --> 45:10.708
<i>‐ With the success</i>
<i>at Vicksburg,</i>

45:10.708 --> 45:12.210
there's no question that Grant

45:12.210 --> 45:14.712
is one of the top
generals in the war.

45:14.712 --> 45:17.006
<i>♪ ♪</i>

45:17.006 --> 45:18.966
<i>Lincoln said,</i>
<i>"He'll be my man</i>

45:18.966 --> 45:21.969
<i>and I'll be his</i>
<i>the rest of the war."</i>

45:21.969 --> 45:26.140
<i>And so Grant is given command</i>
<i>of the entire western theater.</i>

45:26.140 --> 45:27.767
<i>♪ ♪</i>

45:27.767 --> 45:31.229
<i>Well, part of that</i>
<i>new command was Chattanooga.</i>

45:31.229 --> 45:33.940
<i>And in Chattanooga,</i>
<i>there was a Union army</i>

45:33.940 --> 45:37.068
<i>that was essentially trapped.</i>

45:37.068 --> 45:40.238
<i>‐ It's at this point</i>
<i>that Lincoln decides</i>

45:40.238 --> 45:42.240
that he must call Grant in
for the situation.

45:42.240 --> 45:44.742
<i>♪ ♪</i>

45:44.742 --> 45:47.745
<i>‐ The art of war</i>
<i>is simple enough.</i>

45:47.745 --> 45:50.122
<i>Find out where your enemy is,</i>

45:50.122 --> 45:52.917
<i>get at him as soon as you can,</i>

45:52.917 --> 45:55.086
<i>strike him as hard as you can,</i>

45:55.086 --> 45:57.421
<i>and keep moving on.</i>

45:57.421 --> 45:58.923
<i>♪ ♪</i>

46:00.925 --> 46:07.890
<i>♪ ♪</i>

46:12.436 --> 46:14.772
<i>‐ By the summer of 1863,</i>

46:14.772 --> 46:17.608
<i>the Union army had moved</i>
<i>all the way through Tennessee</i>

46:17.608 --> 46:21.028
<i>and captured Chattanooga.</i>

46:21.028 --> 46:24.532
<i>The Union army</i>
<i>then moved into Georgia,</i>

46:24.532 --> 46:29.620
<i>but the Confederates lashed</i>
<i>back and won a huge victory.</i>

46:29.620 --> 46:32.999
<i>The Union army retreated</i>
<i>back into Chattanooga.</i>

46:32.999 --> 46:35.459
<i>The Confederates followed,</i>
<i>occupying the heights</i>

46:35.459 --> 46:37.628
<i>around the city.</i>

46:37.628 --> 46:39.422
And U. S. Grant is brought
into Chattanooga

46:39.422 --> 46:41.507
to do what he does best...

46:41.507 --> 46:43.467
<i>win.</i>

46:43.467 --> 46:45.803
<i>♪ ♪</i>

46:45.803 --> 46:49.432
‐ He's essentially being
brought in as a kind of fixer.

46:49.432 --> 46:53.311
<i>Here's the guy who won</i>
<i>the campaign at Vicksburg,</i>

46:53.311 --> 46:56.731
and he's being asked
to do it again.

46:56.731 --> 46:59.191
<i>The Union Army</i>
<i>of the Cumberland is stuck</i>

46:59.191 --> 47:01.027
<i>down in this valley,</i>

47:01.027 --> 47:05.323
<i>trapped in a siege,</i>
<i>and starving.</i>

47:05.323 --> 47:07.074
<i>The Confederate army</i>
<i>has set up</i>

47:07.074 --> 47:09.744
<i>a ring around the city</i>

47:09.744 --> 47:12.913
<i>that gives them a commanding</i>
<i>artillery position.</i>

47:12.913 --> 47:17.710
<i>♪ ♪</i>

47:17.710 --> 47:20.671
<i>It's incredibly high stakes.</i>

47:20.671 --> 47:23.382
<i>By holding Chattanooga,</i>
<i>you hold one of the most</i>

47:23.382 --> 47:27.678
<i>important rail networks</i>
<i>in Tennessee.</i>

47:27.678 --> 47:30.264
<i>Grant knew if you can</i>
<i>hold that rail hub,</i>

47:30.264 --> 47:32.600
<i>you can build up</i>
<i>a massive effort</i>

47:32.600 --> 47:36.020
<i>to invade the Deep South.</i>

47:36.020 --> 47:37.438
The loss of Chattanooga
would've set

47:37.438 --> 47:39.357
the Union war effort
back months,

47:39.357 --> 47:40.691
if not years.

47:40.691 --> 47:42.693
<i>♪ ♪</i>

47:42.693 --> 47:45.696
<i>‐ His first concern</i>
<i>is to feed his troops</i>

47:45.696 --> 47:47.823
<i>by winning a small engagement</i>
<i>on the Confederate side</i>

47:47.823 --> 47:49.283
<i>of the Tennessee River</i>

47:49.283 --> 47:53.412
<i>to open up his new</i>
<i>supply line.</i>

47:53.412 --> 47:55.164
Then, like any boss
that comes into a new company,

47:55.164 --> 47:57.541
Grant wants his people.

47:57.541 --> 48:00.044
<i>And he immediately calls</i>
<i>the four divisions</i>

48:00.044 --> 48:04.215
<i>of William Tecumseh Sherman</i>
<i>to come to Chattanooga.</i>

48:04.215 --> 48:06.509
‐ The intention then
is to seize the initiative

48:06.509 --> 48:08.260
and make an attack
against the Confederates

48:08.260 --> 48:10.221
and drive them
away from Chattanooga.

48:10.221 --> 48:15.059
<i>♪ ♪</i>

48:15.059 --> 48:17.061
<i>‐ During the battle</i>
<i>of Chattanooga,</i>

48:17.061 --> 48:20.523
Grant is commanding
multiple armies.

48:20.523 --> 48:23.109
<i>He's got Sherman with</i>
<i>the Army of the Tennessee.</i>

48:23.109 --> 48:26.070
<i>He has George Thomas with</i>
<i>the Army of the Cumberland.</i>

48:26.070 --> 48:27.655
<i>He also has Joseph Hooker,</i>

48:27.655 --> 48:30.282
<i>who's coming in</i>
<i>from the eastern theater.</i>

48:30.282 --> 48:32.827
<i>‐ The idea was that</i>
<i>Hooker would flank</i>

48:32.827 --> 48:35.121
<i>the Confederate position</i>
<i>from the south,</i>

48:35.121 --> 48:37.123
<i>Sherman would bring his army</i>

48:37.123 --> 48:38.916
<i>to the northern flank,</i>

48:38.916 --> 48:41.710
<i>and George Thomas</i>
<i>would assault the center.</i>

48:41.710 --> 48:45.589
<i>Three separate assaults</i>
<i>of one position.</i>

48:45.589 --> 48:48.592
[soldiers clamoring,
gunfire]

48:48.592 --> 48:55.599
<i>♪ ♪</i>

48:55.599 --> 48:58.102
[soldier yelling indistinctly]

48:58.102 --> 49:05.151
<i>♪ ♪</i>

49:10.239 --> 49:11.574
‐ Sir.

49:14.118 --> 49:16.370
From General Sherman
on Missionary Ridge.

49:16.370 --> 49:19.957
<i>♪ ♪</i>

49:19.957 --> 49:22.793
<i>‐ At Chattanooga,</i>
<i>his battle plan doesn't work</i>

49:22.793 --> 49:24.628
<i>the way he expected it to,</i>

49:24.628 --> 49:27.298
<i>but he's got</i>
<i>the presence of mind</i>

49:27.298 --> 49:30.509
to process it
and make decisions

49:30.509 --> 49:34.472
and adapt to things that
he didn't expect to happen.

49:34.472 --> 49:37.349
[gunfire]

49:37.349 --> 49:38.809
<i>‐ Sherman's stuck.</i>

49:38.809 --> 49:41.645
Send in Thomas' men.

49:41.645 --> 49:45.357
Order them to attack the rifle
pits below Missionary Ridge.

49:45.357 --> 49:48.319
<i>Sherman needs our help‐‐</i>
<i>now.</i>

49:48.319 --> 49:51.363
<i>♪ ♪</i>

49:51.363 --> 49:54.825
<i>‐ George Thomas' army</i>
<i>had been much maligned</i>

49:54.825 --> 49:58.162
<i>for having been trapped</i>
<i>in a siege,</i>

49:58.162 --> 50:00.831
and I think those men
were spoiling for a fight

50:00.831 --> 50:03.000
as a result.

50:03.000 --> 50:05.586
[soldiers clamoring,
gunfire]

50:05.586 --> 50:09.507
<i>♪ ♪</i>

50:09.507 --> 50:12.176
<i>‐ Grant gives the order</i>
<i>with the hope that that will</i>

50:12.176 --> 50:15.012
<i>force the Confederates</i>
<i>to start moving troops</i>

50:15.012 --> 50:17.014
<i>away from Sherman's path.</i>

50:17.014 --> 50:20.351
<i>♪ ♪</i>

50:20.351 --> 50:23.354
<i>The order was that once</i>
<i>they seized the rifle pits,</i>

50:23.354 --> 50:25.689
<i>they should stop, reorganize,</i>

50:25.689 --> 50:30.236
<i>and then attack the top</i>
<i>of Missionary Ridge.</i>

50:30.236 --> 50:33.197
<i>But they don't stop.</i>

50:33.197 --> 50:40.204
<i>♪ ♪</i>

50:40.204 --> 50:44.041
[soldiers yelling]

50:44.041 --> 50:46.919
<i>♪ ♪</i>

50:46.919 --> 50:49.380
<i>‐ Without awaiting</i>
<i>further orders,</i>

50:49.380 --> 50:53.050
<i>on our troops went</i>
<i>for the crest.</i>

50:53.050 --> 50:56.220
<i>♪ ♪</i>

50:56.220 --> 50:59.348
<i>The fire along</i>
<i>the rebel line was terrific.</i>

50:59.348 --> 51:03.727
<i>Cannon and musket balls</i>
<i>filled the air.</i>

51:03.727 --> 51:06.897
<i>The pursuit continued</i>
<i>until the crest was reached.</i>

51:06.897 --> 51:13.654
<i>♪ ♪</i>

51:13.654 --> 51:16.949
<i>‐ It was a fantastic</i>
<i>victory for Grant.</i>

51:16.949 --> 51:19.493
<i>This is the battle</i>
<i>that really, I think, makes</i>

51:19.493 --> 51:24.832
the Republic respect Grant
as the possible savior.

51:24.832 --> 51:27.376
<i>♪ ♪</i>

51:27.376 --> 51:31.088
<i>‐ News of this goes through</i>
<i>the North as a great triumph.</i>

51:31.088 --> 51:33.924
Grant is now clearly
and unambiguously

51:33.924 --> 51:36.594
<i>the general who looks like</i>

51:36.594 --> 51:38.929
<i>finally the man</i>
<i>who can win this war.</i>

51:38.929 --> 51:41.056
<i>♪ ♪</i>

51:41.056 --> 51:44.310
<i>‐ Grant has eliminated two</i>
<i>Confederate armies via siege,</i>

51:44.310 --> 51:47.563
<i>Fort Donelson and Vicksburg.</i>

51:47.563 --> 51:49.648
At Chattanooga, he combined
three disparate armies

51:49.648 --> 51:51.108
into a single effort,

51:51.108 --> 51:54.278
so his technical competencies
were beyond reproach.

51:54.278 --> 51:55.654
<i>♪ ♪</i>

51:55.654 --> 51:58.115
<i>‐ At Chattanooga,</i>
<i>he reverses another</i>

51:58.115 --> 52:01.785
<i>very desperate situation</i>
<i>for the Union forces.</i>

52:01.785 --> 52:04.622
That's what ultimately
then leads Lincoln

52:04.622 --> 52:06.040
to bring Grant east.

52:06.040 --> 52:08.334
<i>♪ ♪</i>

52:08.334 --> 52:10.961
<i>‐ By March of 1864,</i>

52:10.961 --> 52:12.963
<i>Lincoln has found his man,</i>

52:12.963 --> 52:15.299
and Congress raises Grant
to the rank

52:15.299 --> 52:17.801
of full lieutenant general,

52:17.801 --> 52:20.512
<i>the first general</i>
<i>since Washington</i>

52:20.512 --> 52:24.141
<i>to hold the full rank</i>
<i>of lieutenant general.</i>

52:24.141 --> 52:25.559
<i>♪ ♪</i>

52:25.559 --> 52:30.147
‐ He is to be in command
of all the Union armies.

52:30.147 --> 52:32.691
<i>This is novel.</i>

52:32.691 --> 52:35.527
<i>‐ The bill restoring the grade</i>
<i>of lieutenant general</i>

52:35.527 --> 52:38.697
<i>of the army had passed.</i>

52:38.697 --> 52:42.159
<i>I was ordered to Washington</i>
<i>to receive my commission.</i>

52:42.159 --> 52:43.661
<i>♪ ♪</i>

52:43.661 --> 52:45.871
<i>‐ Grant and Lincoln never meet</i>
<i>each other face‐to‐face</i>

52:45.871 --> 52:48.082
<i>until Grant shows up</i>
<i>in Washington</i>

52:48.082 --> 52:51.502
<i>to be promoted</i>
<i>to lieutenant general...</i>

52:51.502 --> 52:53.337
<i>but his ability</i>
<i>to advise Lincoln</i>

52:53.337 --> 52:55.339
<i>and to guide</i>
<i>the whole nation's effort</i>

52:55.339 --> 52:57.257
<i>to win the war...</i>

52:57.257 --> 52:59.802
<i>that was a question mark.</i>

53:01.720 --> 53:08.686
[knock <i>♪ ♪d</i> oor]

53:11.772 --> 53:13.816
‐ Mr. President.

53:15.359 --> 53:18.320
‐ General Grant.

53:18.320 --> 53:20.406
Come in.

53:20.406 --> 53:23.117
Come in.

53:23.117 --> 53:27.496
<i>♪ ♪</i>

53:27.496 --> 53:29.915
I do not profess
to be a military man,

53:29.915 --> 53:33.919
and I certainly would
never interfere, but...

53:33.919 --> 53:35.838
<i>♪ ♪</i>

53:35.838 --> 53:37.548
Here it is.

53:42.261 --> 53:45.055
I've marked
our current placements.

53:45.055 --> 53:46.473
Now...

53:46.473 --> 53:48.016
if we move into Virginia

53:48.016 --> 53:50.102
between the course
of these two rivers,

53:50.102 --> 53:53.105
we can not only use them
to bring in supplies.

53:53.105 --> 53:55.858
We might also protect
our flanks.

53:57.276 --> 53:59.278
‐ I'll consider it, sir.

53:59.278 --> 54:05.701
<i>♪ ♪</i>

54:05.701 --> 54:09.413
‐ Of course.

54:09.413 --> 54:11.457
But tell me...

54:11.457 --> 54:13.751
<i>♪ ♪</i>

54:13.751 --> 54:17.880
You'll go after Lee?

54:17.880 --> 54:21.884
You'll go after him
until he's finished?

54:21.884 --> 54:23.844
It all depends on you.

54:23.844 --> 54:29.308
<i>♪ ♪</i>

54:29.308 --> 54:32.186
<i>‐ The president told me</i>
<i>that all he had ever wanted</i>

54:32.186 --> 54:34.855
<i>was someone who would</i>
<i>take responsibility</i>

54:34.855 --> 54:36.190
<i>and act.</i>

54:36.190 --> 54:41.737
<i>♪ ♪</i>

54:41.737 --> 54:43.489
<i>‐ Lincoln had gone</i>
<i>through about every other</i>

54:43.489 --> 54:45.449
<i>senior general</i>
<i>in the Union army</i>

54:45.449 --> 54:47.284
<i>at this point in time.</i>

54:47.284 --> 54:49.411
<i>And finally,</i>
<i>Lincoln finds his general,</i>

54:49.411 --> 54:52.206
<i>a general who will</i>
<i>actually fight.</i>

54:52.206 --> 54:54.541
<i>And Grant is truly</i>
<i>one of the great</i>

54:54.541 --> 54:58.045
<i>battle captains of all time.</i>

54:58.045 --> 55:01.965
He is someone
who achieved brilliance,

55:01.965 --> 55:04.676
tactically, operationally,
and strategically.

55:04.676 --> 55:06.261
[artillery firing,
soldiers yelling]

55:06.261 --> 55:08.972
<i>At the tactical level,</i>
<i>this would be commanding</i>

55:08.972 --> 55:12.518
<i>multiple brigades like</i>
<i>Fort Henry and Fort Donelson</i>

55:12.518 --> 55:15.020
in the early stages
of the war in the west.

55:15.020 --> 55:18.357
[soldiers yelling]

55:18.357 --> 55:21.568
<i>Operationally, this is</i>
<i>multiple divisions now.</i>

55:21.568 --> 55:24.279
<i>And, of course,</i>
<i>Vicksburg is an extraordinary</i>

55:24.279 --> 55:26.490
<i>example of that.</i>

55:26.490 --> 55:28.200
And then strategically,

55:28.200 --> 55:29.785
<i>when he comes east,</i>

55:29.785 --> 55:32.829
<i>he for the first time</i>
<i>then develops</i>

55:32.829 --> 55:36.708
a true strategic campaign
for all of the Union forces.

55:36.708 --> 55:39.711
<i>♪ ♪</i>

55:39.711 --> 55:42.047
<i>‐ Grant's idea when</i>
<i>he becomes commanding general</i>

55:42.047 --> 55:46.510
<i>is to get all of the Union</i>
<i>forces to act in harmony.</i>

55:46.510 --> 55:48.929
<i>He wants to move</i>
<i>on Mobile Bay,</i>

55:48.929 --> 55:51.348
<i>one of the last</i>
<i>Confederate ports.</i>

55:51.348 --> 55:55.018
<i>He wants Sherman</i>
<i>to advance on Atlanta.</i>

55:55.018 --> 55:56.770
<i>♪ ♪</i>

55:56.770 --> 55:59.147
<i>He wants Franz Sigel to go</i>
<i>down the Shenandoah Valley,</i>

55:59.147 --> 56:02.442
<i>the breadbasket of</i>
<i>the Confederacy in the east.</i>

56:02.442 --> 56:04.486
<i>Benjamin Butler will</i>
<i>come up the James River</i>

56:04.486 --> 56:06.113
<i>and get at Richmond</i>
<i>from the south,</i>

56:06.113 --> 56:08.365
<i>hopefully dividing</i>
<i>some of Lee's attention.</i>

56:08.365 --> 56:09.992
<i>And then finally,</i>
<i>the Army of the Potomac</i>

56:09.992 --> 56:12.995
<i>will head at Robert E. Lee</i>
<i>in Richmond.</i>

56:12.995 --> 56:15.581
It's those five pieces
acting in concert

56:15.581 --> 56:17.541
that is his original vision
for how this war

56:17.541 --> 56:19.251
should come to a close.

56:19.251 --> 56:21.837
<i>♪ ♪</i>

56:21.837 --> 56:23.589
<i>‐ The South had become</i>
<i>very good,</i>

56:23.589 --> 56:25.674
with the smaller population,

56:25.674 --> 56:28.093
at moving troops
from one place to another.

56:28.093 --> 56:29.511
<i>♪ ♪</i>

56:29.511 --> 56:31.346
<i>What Grant realized was that</i>

56:31.346 --> 56:34.891
if you simultaneously attack
many Confederate positions,

56:34.891 --> 56:36.935
they would not be able
to play this game.

56:36.935 --> 56:38.395
<i>♪ ♪</i>

56:38.395 --> 56:42.357
<i>‐ Grant's strategic genius</i>
<i>was the ability to move</i>

56:42.357 --> 56:46.028
five different armies
simultaneously...

56:46.028 --> 56:48.322
<i>but also,</i>
<i>Grant recognized,</i>

56:48.322 --> 56:51.074
<i>the destruction</i>
<i>of Robert E. Lee's army,</i>

56:51.074 --> 56:53.493
<i>the symbol</i>
<i>of Confederate nationalism,</i>

56:53.493 --> 56:57.122
<i>was fundamental</i>
<i>to winning the war.</i>

56:57.122 --> 57:00.167
<i>♪ ♪</i>

57:00.167 --> 57:02.419
<i>‐ Robert E. Lee's army</i>
<i>had countless times</i>

57:02.419 --> 57:04.338
<i>defeated Union armies</i>
<i>on the battlefield</i>

57:04.338 --> 57:06.798
with brilliant
tactical maneuvers,

57:06.798 --> 57:09.676
<i>so there was a confidence.</i>

57:09.676 --> 57:11.136
<i>There was an esprit de corps</i>

57:11.136 --> 57:13.597
<i>that bound that army together,</i>

57:13.597 --> 57:16.475
<i>and spirits are high</i>
<i>and ready for an engagement.</i>

57:16.475 --> 57:19.311
<i>♪ ♪</i>

57:19.311 --> 57:21.188
<i>Robert E. Lee</i>
<i>is born the scion</i>

57:21.188 --> 57:24.274
<i>to two of the oldest</i>
<i>elite families</i>

57:24.274 --> 57:25.609
<i>of the state of Virginia.</i>

57:25.609 --> 57:27.152
<i>♪ ♪</i>

57:27.152 --> 57:29.613
<i>And in many ways,</i>
<i>Robert E. Lee becomes</i>

57:29.613 --> 57:31.073
<i>the general most connected</i>

57:31.073 --> 57:32.866
with the institution
of slavery

57:32.866 --> 57:35.744
and protecting
that institution.

57:35.744 --> 57:38.872
<i>‐ Grant had none</i>
<i>of that mystique.</i>

57:38.872 --> 57:41.667
There was no illusion
of a guy,

57:41.667 --> 57:45.170
you know, who was highborn
in the way that Lee was.

57:45.170 --> 57:47.589
<i>But, you know, when I see you</i>
<i>on the battlefield,</i>

57:47.589 --> 57:49.299
<i>none of that matters.</i>

57:49.299 --> 57:51.927
<i>It's just me and you.</i>

57:51.927 --> 57:53.720
<i>‐ But all of Grant's</i>
<i>success had been</i>

57:53.720 --> 57:56.556
<i>in the western theater.</i>

57:56.556 --> 57:59.685
<i>And everybody would argue...</i>

57:59.685 --> 58:00.894
you're not out
in the western theater anymore.

58:00.894 --> 58:03.480
You're fighting Robert E. Lee.

58:03.480 --> 58:05.607
<i>Of course, we could flip</i>
<i>that coin and say</i>

58:05.607 --> 58:09.861
<i>Robert E. Lee is now</i>
<i>fighting Ulysses S. Grant.</i>

58:09.861 --> 58:14.908
<i>♪ ♪</i>

58:14.908 --> 58:17.869
<i>‐ Grant is gonna</i>
<i>personally attach himself</i>

58:17.869 --> 58:20.789
<i>to George Gordon Meade's</i>
<i>Army the of Potomac,</i>

58:20.789 --> 58:23.208
<i>which is gonna</i>
<i>latch on like a bulldog</i>

58:23.208 --> 58:26.753
<i>to Robert E. Lee's</i>
<i>Army of Northern Virginia.</i>

58:26.753 --> 58:28.088
<i>♪ ♪</i>

58:28.088 --> 58:29.798
<i>‐ When Grant comes</i>
<i>down to Brandy Station</i>

58:29.798 --> 58:33.218
<i>to visit the headquarters</i>
<i>of George Gordon Meade,</i>

58:33.218 --> 58:36.888
<i>Meade's staff are surprised.</i>

58:36.888 --> 58:40.100
This was a slightly
ordinary figure

58:40.100 --> 58:44.896
who looked like a merchant
who'd just come from a store.

58:44.896 --> 58:47.399
<i>But then you met his eye,</i>

58:47.399 --> 58:51.987
<i>that icy cold eye that Grant</i>
<i>could somehow have,</i>

58:51.987 --> 58:53.488
<i>and suddenly you knew</i>
<i>this man</i>

58:53.488 --> 58:56.324
<i>was totally in charge</i>
<i>of things.</i>

58:56.324 --> 58:59.244
<i>One clerk was advised,</i>

58:59.244 --> 59:02.622
"When Grant gives you
a straight order, obey it.

59:02.622 --> 59:04.374
"When you have
information for Grant,

59:04.374 --> 59:06.543
"give it to him straight.

59:06.543 --> 59:11.590
"And above all,
don't say 'sir' too much.

59:11.590 --> 59:13.592
<i>Grant's not interested</i>
<i>in that."</i>

59:13.592 --> 59:16.803
<i>♪ ♪</i>

59:16.803 --> 59:20.974
<i>‐ Through most of the winter</i>
<i>of 1863 and 1864,</i>

59:20.974 --> 59:22.851
<i>the Union army</i>
<i>and the Confederates</i>

59:22.851 --> 59:24.436
<i>have been glaring</i>
<i>at each other,</i>

59:24.436 --> 59:27.063
<i>waiting for the spring to come</i>

59:27.063 --> 59:29.691
so that the new campaign
can begin.

59:29.691 --> 59:32.778
<i>Grant wants to get south</i>
<i>so he can engage</i>

59:32.778 --> 59:35.489
<i>Confederates</i>
<i>in more open ground.</i>

59:35.489 --> 59:37.949
<i>But before he does that,</i>
<i>he has to go across</i>

59:37.949 --> 59:40.744
<i>the Rapidan River</i>
<i>and go through an area</i>

59:40.744 --> 59:44.664
<i>deemed as almost Lee's hunting</i>
<i>ground for Union armies...</i>

59:44.664 --> 59:46.416
<i>"The Wilderness."</i>

59:50.712 --> 59:54.216
‐ Gentlemen?

59:54.216 --> 59:57.219
‐ Grant may have won
some victories in the west,

59:57.219 --> 1:00:00.263
but this is Virginia.

1:00:00.263 --> 1:00:02.098
‐ We're strong here, sir.

1:00:02.098 --> 1:00:03.850
And if he attacks,

1:00:03.850 --> 1:00:05.936
we can make a play
for Washington.

1:00:05.936 --> 1:00:07.896
‐ And if he crosses
the Rapidan,

1:00:07.896 --> 1:00:10.690
he'd have to cut
through the Wilderness.

1:00:10.690 --> 1:00:14.402
I can't imagine
he'd be fool enough.

1:00:14.402 --> 1:00:16.530
We'd whip him but good.

1:00:16.530 --> 1:00:18.406
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:00:18.406 --> 1:00:21.618
‐ General Longstreet?

1:00:21.618 --> 1:00:25.288
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:00:25.288 --> 1:00:29.918
‐ I know Grant
from West Point and Mexico.

1:00:29.918 --> 1:00:33.088
Do not underestimate him.

1:00:33.088 --> 1:00:35.382
He will fight us every day
and every hour

1:00:35.382 --> 1:00:37.843
till the end of this war.

1:00:37.843 --> 1:00:39.970
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:00:39.970 --> 1:00:41.805
<i>‐ There's sort of a sense</i>
<i>that, "Okay,</i>

1:00:41.805 --> 1:00:45.183
Robert E. Lee is the champion
of the eastern theater."

1:00:45.183 --> 1:00:46.893
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:00:46.893 --> 1:00:49.062
<i>"And we've tried challenger</i>
<i>after challenger</i>

1:00:49.062 --> 1:00:51.022
<i>"after challenger.</i>

1:00:51.022 --> 1:00:54.192
<i>But now we're bringing in</i>
<i>our best guy from the west."</i>

1:00:54.192 --> 1:00:56.319
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:00:56.319 --> 1:00:58.321
<i>There's huge expectations.</i>

1:00:58.321 --> 1:00:59.990
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:00:59.990 --> 1:01:03.577
<i>‐ I know Lee</i>
<i>as well as he knows himself.</i>

1:01:03.577 --> 1:01:05.829
<i>I intend to attack</i>
<i>his weak points</i>

1:01:05.829 --> 1:01:07.831
<i>and flank his strong ones.</i>

1:01:07.831 --> 1:01:10.584
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:01:12.794 --> 1:01:15.171
<i>‐</i> We have two choices:

1:01:15.171 --> 1:01:17.382
flank Lee and get to Richmond
from the west,

1:01:17.382 --> 1:01:19.676
which leaves
Washington exposed,

1:01:19.676 --> 1:01:21.428
or head south,

1:01:21.428 --> 1:01:23.054
get to Lee by going
through the Wilderness.

1:01:23.054 --> 1:01:24.514
‐ The rebs know those woods.

1:01:24.514 --> 1:01:26.391
Could be deadly for us
to go through there.

1:01:26.391 --> 1:01:28.351
‐ We have to move quickly,
get out the other side,

1:01:28.351 --> 1:01:29.853
meet him in the open.
‐ It's a trap.

1:01:29.853 --> 1:01:32.272
We'd be leaving
Washington undefended.

1:01:32.272 --> 1:01:33.607
‐ General Meade?

1:01:33.607 --> 1:01:35.358
‐ I beat Lee at Gettysburg.

1:01:35.358 --> 1:01:37.402
I'd like to finish the job.

1:01:37.402 --> 1:01:39.529
‐ Then wherever he goes,
you'll follow.

1:01:39.529 --> 1:01:44.200
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:01:44.200 --> 1:01:47.203
We'll cross the Rapidan
into the Wilderness.

1:01:47.203 --> 1:01:52.709
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:01:52.709 --> 1:01:54.628
<i>‐</i> General, our scouts
report he crossed

1:01:54.628 --> 1:01:56.963
the Rapidan last night.

1:01:56.963 --> 1:01:59.716
His army is twice ours, sir.

1:01:59.716 --> 1:02:02.385
‐ We'll just have
to even the odds.

1:02:02.385 --> 1:02:03.762
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:02:03.762 --> 1:02:06.389
Catch them before they
get through the Wilderness.

1:02:06.389 --> 1:02:08.058
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:02:08.058 --> 1:02:11.603
Have General Hill advance
on the Orange Plank Road.

1:02:11.603 --> 1:02:14.731
General Ewell,
on the turnpike.

1:02:14.731 --> 1:02:17.067
‐ Yes, sir.

1:02:17.067 --> 1:02:24.032
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:02:24.032 --> 1:02:26.284
<i>‐ The wilderness</i>
<i>of Spotsylvania</i>

1:02:26.284 --> 1:02:31.831
<i>was 70 square miles</i>
<i>of dense forest.</i>

1:02:31.831 --> 1:02:34.793
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:02:34.793 --> 1:02:37.253
<i>It was difficult</i>
<i>for mass groups</i>

1:02:37.253 --> 1:02:39.047
of soldiers to move through

1:02:39.047 --> 1:02:41.091
this particular area
of Virginia.

1:02:41.091 --> 1:02:43.426
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:02:43.426 --> 1:02:46.596
<i>‐ A little further south</i>
<i>is Spotsylvania Courthouse.</i>

1:02:46.596 --> 1:02:49.182
<i>The land around that area</i>
<i>is a lot more wide open.</i>

1:02:49.182 --> 1:02:52.435
<i>So Grant says, "We need</i>
<i>to cross the Rapidan River</i>

1:02:52.435 --> 1:02:54.437
<i>"and move through</i>
<i>the Wilderness,</i>

1:02:54.437 --> 1:02:57.607
<i>"get to this wide‐open ground</i>
<i>closer to Richmond,</i>

1:02:57.607 --> 1:02:59.651
<i>"and in doing so,</i>

1:02:59.651 --> 1:03:01.319
"Lee's gonna have
to come out and fight us

1:03:01.319 --> 1:03:02.612
and on ground of our choosing."

1:03:02.612 --> 1:03:05.448
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:03:05.448 --> 1:03:08.952
<i>‐ Lee knew this ground.</i>
<i>He knew it well.</i>

1:03:08.952 --> 1:03:10.996
He was going to use
every tree

1:03:10.996 --> 1:03:16.626
and every bush to try
to delay Grant's actions.

1:03:16.626 --> 1:03:18.461
<i>‐ The great advantage</i>
<i>of the Union army</i>

1:03:18.461 --> 1:03:19.796
against
the Army of Northern Virginia

1:03:19.796 --> 1:03:22.799
is in numbers and artillery.

1:03:22.799 --> 1:03:26.136
<i>In that choked vine forest,</i>

1:03:26.136 --> 1:03:27.804
<i>numbers matter less,</i>

1:03:27.804 --> 1:03:31.599
<i>and you cannot bring</i>
<i>your artillery to bear.</i>

1:03:31.599 --> 1:03:33.476
<i>In fact,</i>
<i>the Army of the Potomac</i>

1:03:33.476 --> 1:03:35.353
<i>fought there</i>
<i>against Robert E. Lee</i>

1:03:35.353 --> 1:03:36.646
<i>at the battle</i>
<i>of Chancellorsville</i>

1:03:36.646 --> 1:03:39.899
<i>earlier in the war</i>
<i>and had lost.</i>

1:03:39.899 --> 1:03:41.151
<i>The battle</i>
<i>of Chancellorsville</i>

1:03:41.151 --> 1:03:43.153
<i>is Robert E. Lee's high point.</i>

1:03:43.153 --> 1:03:46.114
<i>Lee is gonna violate all kind</i>
<i>of military principles,</i>

1:03:46.114 --> 1:03:48.658
<i>divide his army in the face</i>
<i>of a larger enemy,</i>

1:03:48.658 --> 1:03:50.827
<i>and, though outnumbered</i>
<i>two to one,</i>

1:03:50.827 --> 1:03:54.581
<i>he will drive the Union army</i>
<i>back across the river.</i>

1:03:54.581 --> 1:03:58.168
<i>This is the magic</i>
<i>of Robert E. Lee.</i>

1:03:58.168 --> 1:03:59.210
‐ The Chancellorsville
battlefield

1:03:59.210 --> 1:04:00.837
and the Wilderness battlefield

1:04:00.837 --> 1:04:04.966
are pretty much
right on top of each other.

1:04:04.966 --> 1:04:08.928
<i>And during the initial phase</i>
<i>of the Wilderness campaign,</i>

1:04:08.928 --> 1:04:10.680
<i>when Grant</i>
<i>and the Army of the Potomac</i>

1:04:10.680 --> 1:04:14.184
<i>cross the river,</i>
<i>they see the remains</i>

1:04:14.184 --> 1:04:17.103
<i>of the battle</i>
<i>of the year before.</i>

1:04:17.103 --> 1:04:24.110
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:04:29.824 --> 1:04:32.702
<i>‐ When Grant was traveling</i>
<i>with the Army of the Potomac,</i>

1:04:32.702 --> 1:04:34.704
he realized the extent
to which Lee

1:04:34.704 --> 1:04:39.042
had gotten into the mind
of all of the officers.

1:04:39.042 --> 1:04:42.921
<i>And he knew that he had</i>
<i>to deal with the Lee mystique.</i>

1:04:42.921 --> 1:04:47.884
<i>That was really one</i>
<i>of his major objectives.</i>

1:04:47.884 --> 1:04:50.136
<i>‐ The natural disposition</i>
<i>of most people</i>

1:04:50.136 --> 1:04:52.514
<i>is to clothe the commander</i>
<i>of a large army</i>

1:04:52.514 --> 1:04:54.224
<i>whom they do not know</i>

1:04:54.224 --> 1:04:57.227
<i>with almost</i>
<i>superhuman abilities.</i>

1:04:57.227 --> 1:05:00.063
<i>But I had known</i>
<i>General Lee personally</i>

1:05:00.063 --> 1:05:03.316
<i>and knew that he was mortal.</i>

1:05:03.316 --> 1:05:04.901
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:05:04.901 --> 1:05:08.238
<i>‐ The Army of the Potomac</i>
<i>numbers about 120,000 men.</i>

1:05:08.238 --> 1:05:13.409
<i>The Confederate army</i>
<i>numbers approximately 62,000.</i>

1:05:13.409 --> 1:05:15.120
<i>Lee knows he's outnumbered,</i>

1:05:15.120 --> 1:05:17.664
<i>but he knows if he can</i>
<i>bottle him up somewhere,</i>

1:05:17.664 --> 1:05:20.750
<i>those superior numbers</i>
<i>won't account for anything.</i>

1:05:20.750 --> 1:05:22.919
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:05:22.919 --> 1:05:25.630
<i>Both sides are confident.</i>

1:05:25.630 --> 1:05:27.757
<i>The Confederates,</i>
<i>they've rebounded</i>

1:05:27.757 --> 1:05:29.926
<i>since their defeat</i>
<i>from Gettysburg.</i>

1:05:29.926 --> 1:05:31.261
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:05:31.261 --> 1:05:33.054
<i>And also,</i>
<i>the Union Army of the Potomac,</i>

1:05:33.054 --> 1:05:34.681
<i>coming off that victory</i>
<i>at Gettysburg,</i>

1:05:34.681 --> 1:05:37.767
<i>they're ready to keep</i>
<i>following up that success.</i>

1:05:37.767 --> 1:05:41.271
That mentality, I think,
explains the ferocity

1:05:41.271 --> 1:05:42.605
of the fighting that follows.

1:05:42.605 --> 1:05:44.983
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:05:44.983 --> 1:05:47.861
<i>‐ We had to have</i>
<i>hard fighting.</i>

1:05:47.861 --> 1:05:49.779
<i>The two armies</i>
<i>now confronting each other</i>

1:05:49.779 --> 1:05:52.824
<i>had been in deadly conflict</i>
<i>for so long</i>

1:05:52.824 --> 1:05:55.618
<i>without any decisive result,</i>

1:05:55.618 --> 1:05:58.872
<i>they hardly knew</i>
<i>which could whip the other.</i>

1:06:02.792 --> 1:06:09.841
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:06:45.627 --> 1:06:48.630
[gunfire, soldiers yelling]

1:06:58.681 --> 1:07:05.021
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:07:07.607 --> 1:07:11.110
<i>‐ So the first time that Grant</i>
<i>and Lee go into battle,</i>

1:07:11.110 --> 1:07:13.029
<i>the two headliners of the war,</i>

1:07:13.029 --> 1:07:14.530
<i>at the Battle</i>
<i>of the Wilderness,</i>

1:07:14.530 --> 1:07:18.910
<i>May of 1864,</i>
<i>Grant crosses into territory</i>

1:07:18.910 --> 1:07:22.121
<i>where Lee</i>
<i>has his army deployed,</i>

1:07:22.121 --> 1:07:24.707
and it's a pretty brutal
fight.

1:07:24.707 --> 1:07:27.252
<i>‐ Lee was actually</i>
<i>moving very aggressively.</i>

1:07:27.252 --> 1:07:29.712
<i>He wanted to attack Grant.</i>

1:07:29.712 --> 1:07:33.258
He wanted to push Grant
out of Virginia.

1:07:33.258 --> 1:07:35.927
<i>‐ Once Grant</i>
<i>crosses the river,</i>

1:07:35.927 --> 1:07:39.722
<i>you see two steely‐eyed</i>
<i>killers who go at each other.</i>

1:07:39.722 --> 1:07:41.474
It's relentless.
It's brutal.

1:07:41.474 --> 1:07:43.559
It's nonstop.
It's exhausting.

1:07:43.559 --> 1:07:46.312
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:07:46.312 --> 1:07:48.356
‐ General Grant,

1:07:48.356 --> 1:07:50.275
Rebel forces are at
the Orange Turnpike

1:07:50.275 --> 1:07:52.986
on the Plank Road.

1:07:52.986 --> 1:07:54.153
‐ Pitch into them
at the first‐‐

1:07:54.153 --> 1:07:55.446
[explosion]

1:07:55.446 --> 1:07:57.240
Pitch into them
at the first opportunity.

1:07:57.240 --> 1:07:59.075
Call the battery and gun crews.

1:07:59.075 --> 1:08:00.535
We'll hold this position.

1:08:00.535 --> 1:08:02.453
<i>‐ Grant is going</i>
<i>to tell Meade,</i>

1:08:02.453 --> 1:08:04.163
"You do not wait
for them to attack you.

1:08:04.163 --> 1:08:06.708
You attack them."

1:08:06.708 --> 1:08:08.293
<i>‐ Why does he do this?</i>

1:08:08.293 --> 1:08:10.420
<i>Because his object</i>
<i>is to go ahead and fight</i>

1:08:10.420 --> 1:08:12.255
<i>Robert E. Lee.</i>

1:08:12.255 --> 1:08:14.465
<i>He takes tactical risk</i>
<i>fighting in the Wilderness</i>

1:08:14.465 --> 1:08:17.260
because there is
a opportunity

1:08:17.260 --> 1:08:19.262
to destroy parts
of Lee's army.

1:08:19.262 --> 1:08:21.014
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:08:21.014 --> 1:08:22.724
<i>‐ It throws Lee for a loop,</i>

1:08:22.724 --> 1:08:25.727
<i>because Lee thought</i>
<i>he had Grant pegged.</i>

1:08:25.727 --> 1:08:27.270
<i>Lee's going off</i>
<i>the old rule book here,</i>

1:08:27.270 --> 1:08:29.897
<i>Union army is not</i>
<i>gonna act aggressively,</i>

1:08:29.897 --> 1:08:31.649
<i>and at the Wilderness,</i>

1:08:31.649 --> 1:08:33.609
<i>that preconceived notion</i>
<i>that he had</i>

1:08:33.609 --> 1:08:36.612
<i>really gets destroyed.</i>

1:08:36.612 --> 1:08:39.782
‐ Grant firmly believes that if
he can retain the initiative,

1:08:39.782 --> 1:08:42.618
he can force the other army
to react to him.

1:08:42.618 --> 1:08:43.995
He believes
the Confederate army

1:08:43.995 --> 1:08:45.246
should march
to a Union drum.

1:08:45.246 --> 1:08:47.915
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:08:47.915 --> 1:08:50.126
<i>Therefore,</i>
<i>he's gonna continue to push</i>

1:08:50.126 --> 1:08:53.254
<i>and drive those Confederates.</i>

1:08:53.254 --> 1:08:56.549
[artillery firing,
soldiers yelling]

1:08:56.549 --> 1:08:58.634
<i>This is not one of those</i>
<i>wide‐open battlefields</i>

1:08:58.634 --> 1:09:01.512
<i>that you can see long lines</i>
<i>of clashing troops.</i>

1:09:01.512 --> 1:09:05.641
<i>Visibility is less</i>
<i>than 20 yards.</i>

1:09:05.641 --> 1:09:07.518
<i>Throw in the smoke</i>
<i>and noise of battle,</i>

1:09:07.518 --> 1:09:10.813
<i>and now it's</i>
<i>even more confusing.</i>

1:09:10.813 --> 1:09:14.233
[soldiers yelling]

1:09:14.233 --> 1:09:17.236
[both grunting]

1:09:24.535 --> 1:09:31.584
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:09:36.381 --> 1:09:39.342
<i>‐ It had been</i>
<i>a very dry spring.</i>

1:09:39.342 --> 1:09:41.969
<i>Now, if you think of men</i>
<i>firing their muskets,</i>

1:09:41.969 --> 1:09:44.389
<i>there's gonna be</i>
<i>a flash of fire,</i>

1:09:44.389 --> 1:09:46.808
and all it takes is one spark.

1:09:46.808 --> 1:09:48.434
[gunshot echoes]

1:09:48.434 --> 1:09:52.188
<i>And the real horrors</i>
<i>of the Wilderness begin.</i>

1:09:52.188 --> 1:09:54.857
<i>The fires are gonna</i>
<i>grow in intensity.</i>

1:09:54.857 --> 1:09:58.069
[soldiers yelling]

1:09:58.069 --> 1:10:05.118
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:10:14.752 --> 1:10:17.380
<i>For the men who are wounded,</i>

1:10:17.380 --> 1:10:19.841
<i>they can either crawl</i>
<i>to the enemy lines,</i>

1:10:19.841 --> 1:10:23.678
<i>or they can always kill</i>
<i>themselves with a revolver.</i>

1:10:23.678 --> 1:10:26.639
<i>For the living soldiers,</i>
<i>at the end of this fight,</i>

1:10:26.639 --> 1:10:29.434
<i>they have to now listen</i>
<i>to men scream to death</i>

1:10:29.434 --> 1:10:32.145
<i>as they're burned alive</i>
<i>in this fire,</i>

1:10:32.145 --> 1:10:34.105
and they now
have to smell their bodies

1:10:34.105 --> 1:10:36.065
as its roasted
in the conflagration,

1:10:36.065 --> 1:10:38.609
and that is something
that truly sticks with them

1:10:38.609 --> 1:10:39.736
for the rest
of their lives.

1:10:39.736 --> 1:10:42.405
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:10:42.405 --> 1:10:45.199
<i>‐ The Wilderness was a brutal,</i>
<i>bloody battle,</i>

1:10:45.199 --> 1:10:46.659
<i>similar to the battle</i>
<i>they'd fought</i>

1:10:46.659 --> 1:10:48.244
<i>at Chancellorsville</i>
<i>the year before,</i>

1:10:48.244 --> 1:10:50.413
<i>almost in the exact same</i>
<i>location.</i>

1:10:50.413 --> 1:10:53.082
And that battle had ended
with the Union army

1:10:53.082 --> 1:10:54.751
pulling back
from the field

1:10:54.751 --> 1:10:57.003
<i>and trying</i>
<i>to regenerate itself</i>

1:10:57.003 --> 1:11:00.631
<i>and get itself</i>
<i>back into condition.</i>

1:11:00.631 --> 1:11:02.592
‐ Grant might have been,
like the other generals,

1:11:02.592 --> 1:11:05.428
justified in breaking off
and pulling back to regroup.

1:11:05.428 --> 1:11:11.225
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:11:21.861 --> 1:11:24.906
‐ General Grant.

1:11:24.906 --> 1:11:26.741
Do you want
the casualty numbers?

1:11:31.078 --> 1:11:33.539
‐ We'll be the first
to attack in the morning.

1:11:34.874 --> 1:11:36.876
‐ Our men are exhausted.

1:11:36.876 --> 1:11:38.711
‐ So are his.

1:11:40.254 --> 1:11:42.757
We go forward.

1:11:42.757 --> 1:11:45.593
Lee's still waiting
for reinforcements.

1:11:45.593 --> 1:11:46.844
So if we're the first
to attack,

1:11:46.844 --> 1:11:48.304
we have our advantage.

1:11:50.014 --> 1:11:51.224
‐ General.

1:11:51.224 --> 1:11:52.725
‐ General Meade.

1:11:54.352 --> 1:11:56.854
Don't forget.

1:11:56.854 --> 1:11:59.440
We possess strengths
they do not have.

1:12:00.942 --> 1:12:04.111
Our numbers...

1:12:04.111 --> 1:12:06.113
and our purpose, Meade.

1:12:06.113 --> 1:12:08.741
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:12:08.741 --> 1:12:10.701
Our purpose.

1:12:10.701 --> 1:12:12.662
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:12:12.662 --> 1:12:15.039
‐ Right, sir.

1:12:15.039 --> 1:12:22.088
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:12:31.889 --> 1:12:38.938
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:13:03.296 --> 1:13:05.590
<i>‐ I was anxious that</i>
<i>the rebels should not take</i>

1:13:05.590 --> 1:13:07.800
<i>the initiative in the morning</i>

1:13:07.800 --> 1:13:10.511
<i>and therefore</i>
<i>ordered an assault.</i>

1:13:10.511 --> 1:13:12.638
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:13:12.638 --> 1:13:15.600
[gunfire echoing]

1:13:15.600 --> 1:13:19.687
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:13:19.687 --> 1:13:23.232
[gunfire]

1:13:23.232 --> 1:13:26.569
[soldiers yelling]

1:13:26.569 --> 1:13:31.991
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:13:31.991 --> 1:13:34.744
<i>‐ Union forces were successful</i>
<i>initially in the morning.</i>

1:13:34.744 --> 1:13:36.787
They catch
the Confederate 3rd Corps

1:13:36.787 --> 1:13:38.831
under A. P. Hill
by surprise,

1:13:38.831 --> 1:13:41.417
<i>they push them a good mile,</i>

1:13:41.417 --> 1:13:45.212
<i>and it looks like Lee's right</i>
<i>flank is about to cave in.</i>

1:13:45.212 --> 1:13:51.594
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:13:51.594 --> 1:13:53.971
‐ General.
‐ We're losing ground.

1:13:53.971 --> 1:13:56.641
‐ But Longstreet's
moving in from the west...

1:13:56.641 --> 1:13:58.351
With the Texas boys.

1:13:58.351 --> 1:14:00.436
‐ And I'm glad of it.

1:14:00.436 --> 1:14:03.439
Those Texas boys will
stand and fight all day.

1:14:03.439 --> 1:14:09.528
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:14:09.528 --> 1:14:12.448
<i>‐ Longstreet has arrived</i>
<i>with reinforcements.</i>

1:14:12.448 --> 1:14:13.950
Lee may counterattack.

1:14:13.950 --> 1:14:15.868
‐ Let him.

1:14:15.868 --> 1:14:17.370
We'll stick it out.

1:14:17.370 --> 1:14:19.372
‐ Let's taken our land,
forced us out.

1:14:19.372 --> 1:14:20.790
He's gonna advance.

1:14:20.790 --> 1:14:24.543
‐ I'm tired of hearing
about what Lee is gonna do.

1:14:24.543 --> 1:14:26.796
Some of you think he's gonna
turn a double somersault

1:14:26.796 --> 1:14:30.675
and land in our rear and both
flanks at the same time.

1:14:30.675 --> 1:14:32.385
Go back to your commands.

1:14:32.385 --> 1:14:34.637
Think about what
we're gonna do.

1:14:34.637 --> 1:14:41.644
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:14:46.649 --> 1:14:51.153
<i>‐ Longstreet arrives to save</i>
<i>the day in the nick of time.</i>

1:14:51.153 --> 1:14:52.405
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:14:52.405 --> 1:14:54.407
<i>James Longstreet</i>
<i>had actually attended</i>

1:14:54.407 --> 1:14:57.493
<i>Ulysses S. Grant's wedding.</i>

1:14:57.493 --> 1:14:59.453
And he is Lee's
most trusted subordinate.

1:14:59.453 --> 1:15:00.997
He is the old warhorse.

1:15:00.997 --> 1:15:03.749
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:15:03.749 --> 1:15:05.668
<i>[gunfire, soldiers yelling]</i>

1:15:05.668 --> 1:15:09.755
<i>‐ The Confederates</i>
<i>slam into Union lines...</i>

1:15:09.755 --> 1:15:12.174
<i>but the Union</i>
<i>had bolstered their defenses.</i>

1:15:12.174 --> 1:15:14.635
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:15:14.635 --> 1:15:18.973
<i>Ultimately,</i>
<i>the series of assaults fail.</i>

1:15:18.973 --> 1:15:21.892
<i>‐ And James Longstreet</i>
<i>will be accidentally wounded</i>

1:15:21.892 --> 1:15:24.687
<i>by his own men,</i>
<i>shot in the neck,</i>

1:15:24.687 --> 1:15:27.565
<i>nearly choking to death</i>
<i>on his own blood</i>

1:15:27.565 --> 1:15:30.860
<i>before he can be moved</i>
<i>from the field.</i>

1:15:30.860 --> 1:15:32.570
[gunfire]

1:15:32.570 --> 1:15:35.573
<i>The Wilderness is on fire.</i>

1:15:35.573 --> 1:15:42.621
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:15:44.290 --> 1:15:45.791
One soldier describes it

1:15:45.791 --> 1:15:49.211
as a battle of invisibles
versus invisibles.

1:15:49.211 --> 1:15:52.548
[soldiers yelling]

1:15:52.548 --> 1:15:54.592
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:15:54.592 --> 1:15:57.720
<i>They could not see</i>
<i>the enemy army.</i>

1:15:57.720 --> 1:16:02.349
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:16:02.349 --> 1:16:05.394
[gunfire]

1:16:07.938 --> 1:16:10.232
<i>Soldiers are trapped.</i>

1:16:10.232 --> 1:16:12.860
<i>They cannot find</i>
<i>their way out.</i>

1:16:12.860 --> 1:16:16.530
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:16:16.530 --> 1:16:18.407
[gunshot]

1:16:18.407 --> 1:16:21.035
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:16:21.035 --> 1:16:24.497
[gunshot]

1:16:24.497 --> 1:16:26.916
‐ [screaming]

1:16:26.916 --> 1:16:29.251
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:16:29.251 --> 1:16:32.088
[gunfire]

1:16:32.088 --> 1:16:35.091
[yelling]

1:16:35.091 --> 1:16:42.098
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:16:47.103 --> 1:16:52.316
<i>‐ The woods were set on fire</i>
<i>by the bursting shells.</i>

1:16:52.316 --> 1:16:54.985
<i>The wounded,</i>
<i>who had not strength to move,</i>

1:16:54.985 --> 1:16:57.988
<i>were either suffocated</i>
<i>or burned to death.</i>

1:16:57.988 --> 1:17:03.452
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:17:03.452 --> 1:17:05.121
<i>‐ By the end</i>
<i>of two days of combat,</i>

1:17:05.121 --> 1:17:07.998
the Union army has sustained
about 17,000 men

1:17:07.998 --> 1:17:10.626
killed, captured,
wounded, or missing.

1:17:10.626 --> 1:17:13.379
<i>Confederates are about 11,000.</i>

1:17:13.379 --> 1:17:16.632
<i>Grant has lost now more men</i>
<i>in the two days at Wilderness</i>

1:17:16.632 --> 1:17:19.135
<i>than he did</i>
<i>in the two days at Shiloh.</i>

1:17:19.135 --> 1:17:21.137
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:17:21.137 --> 1:17:24.849
<i>‐</i> This was a particularly
horrifying battle...

1:17:24.849 --> 1:17:27.143
<i>not only because</i>
<i>of the number of casualties,</i>

1:17:27.143 --> 1:17:29.353
<i>but the forest is burning.</i>

1:17:29.353 --> 1:17:33.023
<i>What that meant was,</i>
<i>Grant went into his tent,</i>

1:17:33.023 --> 1:17:36.819
<i>flung himself down on the cot.</i>

1:17:36.819 --> 1:17:38.320
<i>There was a need for some</i>

1:17:38.320 --> 1:17:40.739
<i>emotional release</i>
<i>or catharsis,</i>

1:17:40.739 --> 1:17:43.033
<i>and Grant had never</i>
<i>shown that side</i>

1:17:43.033 --> 1:17:46.328
<i>of his character before.</i>

1:17:46.328 --> 1:17:49.540
[fire roaring,
soldiers yelling]

1:17:49.540 --> 1:17:53.669
<i>‐ Our losses</i>
<i>in the Wilderness were severe.</i>

1:17:53.669 --> 1:17:56.714
<i>We could claim no victory</i>
<i>over the enemy,</i>

1:17:56.714 --> 1:17:59.717
<i>neither did they gain</i>
<i>a single advantage.</i>

1:17:59.717 --> 1:18:03.012
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:18:03.012 --> 1:18:06.015
[indistinct chatter]

1:18:13.564 --> 1:18:17.026
‐ We have 'em hell,
General Lee.

1:18:17.026 --> 1:18:19.653
‐ They gave us the same.

1:18:19.653 --> 1:18:21.655
‐ I'm told Longstreet
will survive.

1:18:24.742 --> 1:18:27.203
Scouts say Grant's packing up.

1:18:27.203 --> 1:18:29.038
Finally retreating, sir.

1:18:29.038 --> 1:18:30.789
We won't see him here again.

1:18:30.789 --> 1:18:32.958
‐ Tell me, Colonel...

1:18:32.958 --> 1:18:35.878
have you ever met Grant?

1:18:35.878 --> 1:18:37.630
‐ No, sir.

1:18:37.630 --> 1:18:39.924
‐ No.

1:18:39.924 --> 1:18:41.926
I didn't think so.

1:18:41.926 --> 1:18:43.344
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:18:43.344 --> 1:18:46.013
If you had,
you know he's not retreating.

1:18:46.013 --> 1:18:47.723
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:18:47.723 --> 1:18:50.226
He's not a retreating man.

1:18:50.226 --> 1:18:56.732
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:19:02.988 --> 1:19:04.782
<i>‐ I now felt the full weight</i>

1:19:04.782 --> 1:19:07.743
<i>of responsibility</i>
<i>on my shoulders.</i>

1:19:07.743 --> 1:19:10.746
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:19:12.748 --> 1:19:18.295
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:19:18.295 --> 1:19:22.091
<i>[soldier shrieking]</i>

1:19:22.091 --> 1:19:24.468
[soldiers yelling]

1:19:24.468 --> 1:19:27.471
[fire crackling,
soldier yells]

1:19:27.471 --> 1:19:30.099
<i>‐ You will go after Lee.</i>

1:19:30.099 --> 1:19:33.936
<i>You will go after him</i>
<i>until he's finished.</i>

1:19:33.936 --> 1:19:35.604
‐ [yelling]

1:19:35.604 --> 1:19:38.107
<i>‐ It all depends on you.</i>

1:19:40.651 --> 1:19:41.986
‐ Gentlemen.

1:19:41.986 --> 1:19:44.113
‐ Come on, boys!
Let's move out!

1:19:44.113 --> 1:19:47.783
[bugle call playing]

1:19:47.783 --> 1:19:51.287
<i>‐ After two days</i>
<i>of the most brutal,</i>

1:19:51.287 --> 1:19:56.250
<i>vicious fighting</i>
<i>in the Wilderness of Virginia,</i>

1:19:56.250 --> 1:19:58.252
soldiers
of the Army of the Potomac

1:19:58.252 --> 1:20:00.170
and their opposite numbers

1:20:00.170 --> 1:20:01.505
in the Army
of Northern Virginia

1:20:01.505 --> 1:20:05.009
had fought themselves
to a standstill.

1:20:05.009 --> 1:20:07.469
<i>Usually when a standstill</i>
<i>like that happened,</i>

1:20:07.469 --> 1:20:09.430
<i>the result was that</i>
<i>the Union army</i>

1:20:09.430 --> 1:20:12.683
<i>would pack its bags and go</i>
<i>back across the Rapidan River,</i>

1:20:12.683 --> 1:20:16.645
<i>as it had happened</i>
<i>literally one year before</i>

1:20:16.645 --> 1:20:19.565
<i>at the battle</i>
<i>of Chancellorsville.</i>

1:20:19.565 --> 1:20:22.443
<i>The question in the minds</i>
<i>of these soldiers was,</i>

1:20:22.443 --> 1:20:24.194
<i>"What direction</i>
<i>is Ulysses Grant</i>

1:20:24.194 --> 1:20:25.571
<i>going to take us?"</i>

1:20:25.571 --> 1:20:31.201
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:20:31.201 --> 1:20:36.248
<i>‐ In war, anything</i>
<i>is better than indecision.</i>

1:20:36.248 --> 1:20:38.834
<i>We must decide.</i>

1:20:38.834 --> 1:20:41.045
<i>If I am wrong,</i>
<i>we shall soon find out</i>

1:20:41.045 --> 1:20:43.505
<i>and can do the other thing.</i>

1:20:43.505 --> 1:20:47.509
<i>Not to decide</i>
<i>may ruin everything.</i>

1:20:47.509 --> 1:20:52.181
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:20:52.181 --> 1:20:56.060
<i>‐ And so Grant arrives</i>
<i>at the critical intersection</i>

1:20:56.060 --> 1:20:59.229
in the Wilderness if he was
going to move farther south

1:20:59.229 --> 1:21:01.023
around Lee's flank,

1:21:01.023 --> 1:21:03.901
<i>seizing the strategic</i>
<i>initiative</i>

1:21:03.901 --> 1:21:07.863
<i>to threaten the Confederate</i>
<i>capital, Richmond.</i>

1:21:07.863 --> 1:21:11.241
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:21:11.241 --> 1:21:13.744
<i>‐ The soldiers</i>
<i>were waiting to see,</i>

1:21:13.744 --> 1:21:17.039
<i>"What direction</i>
<i>is he going to take?</i>

1:21:17.039 --> 1:21:19.124
<i>"If he turns to the left,</i>

1:21:19.124 --> 1:21:21.418
<i>"we're gonna be retreating</i>
<i>back across the river.</i>

1:21:21.418 --> 1:21:22.878
<i>"If he turns right,</i>

1:21:22.878 --> 1:21:24.630
<i>that means</i>
<i>we're heading south."</i>

1:21:24.630 --> 1:21:28.217
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:21:28.217 --> 1:21:29.885
<i>‐ We're going south!</i>

1:21:29.885 --> 1:21:31.720
‐ Heading south?
‐ To Richmond.

1:21:31.720 --> 1:21:34.056
‐ Richmond?
‐ To Richmond.

1:21:34.056 --> 1:21:36.266
‐ We're heading south.
‐ We're headed south!

1:21:36.266 --> 1:21:39.228
[soldiers yelling and cheering]

1:21:39.228 --> 1:21:45.734
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:21:49.446 --> 1:21:51.407
<i>‐ Suddenly,</i>
<i>to their astonishment,</i>

1:21:51.407 --> 1:21:54.576
<i>they're all wheeling</i>
<i>around to the south.</i>

1:21:54.576 --> 1:21:57.079
<i>And it took tremendous</i>
<i>courage and tremendous</i>

1:21:57.079 --> 1:22:00.124
<i>personal fortitude</i>
<i>on Grant's part</i>

1:22:00.124 --> 1:22:03.627
<i>because Union casualties</i>
<i>were higher at the Wilderness</i>

1:22:03.627 --> 1:22:06.880
<i>than Confederate casualties...</i>

1:22:06.880 --> 1:22:10.968
but Grant always had this
ultimate faith in victory.

1:22:10.968 --> 1:22:14.012
<i>And I think that there are</i>
<i>certain generals in history,</i>

1:22:14.012 --> 1:22:15.722
<i>when they have</i>
<i>that faith in victory,</i>

1:22:15.722 --> 1:22:18.267
<i>it's something</i>
<i>that communicates itself</i>

1:22:18.267 --> 1:22:19.435
<i>to the troops.</i>

1:22:19.435 --> 1:22:22.938
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:22:22.938 --> 1:22:26.442
<i>‐ At Wilderness,</i>
<i>that is a tactical loss,</i>

1:22:26.442 --> 1:22:28.444
<i>and yet Grant stands</i>
<i>at those crossroads</i>

1:22:28.444 --> 1:22:31.280
<i>and goes,</i>
<i>"This is not a loss.</i>

1:22:31.280 --> 1:22:33.782
<i>This is the first step</i>
<i>to the end of the war."</i>

1:22:33.782 --> 1:22:36.034
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:22:36.034 --> 1:22:38.454
<i>So as he heads south,</i>
<i>Grant will fight</i>

1:22:38.454 --> 1:22:42.666
<i>in a scope and scale</i>
<i>beyond anybody's experience.</i>

1:22:42.666 --> 1:22:44.960
We actually see the changing
character of war here.

1:22:44.960 --> 1:22:46.628
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:22:46.628 --> 1:22:48.464
<i>Technology starts</i>
<i>to be a big part of it:</i>

1:22:48.464 --> 1:22:52.009
<i>steam engines, ironclads,</i>

1:22:52.009 --> 1:22:55.471
<i>railroads, telegraph.</i>

1:22:55.471 --> 1:22:59.308
<i>However, there is this</i>
<i>unchanging nature of war.</i>

1:22:59.308 --> 1:23:01.143
<i>It's still a clash of wills.</i>

1:23:01.143 --> 1:23:05.564
<i>There's still</i>
<i>fear and interest.</i>

1:23:05.564 --> 1:23:09.318
<i>There's still hope</i>
<i>about what might happen.</i>

1:23:09.318 --> 1:23:14.198
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:23:14.198 --> 1:23:15.866
<i>When you think</i>
<i>about the Civil War,</i>

1:23:15.866 --> 1:23:17.367
<i>we say that</i>
<i>Confederates are fighting</i>

1:23:17.367 --> 1:23:19.369
<i>for hearth and home</i>

1:23:19.369 --> 1:23:21.497
<i>and for this cause</i>
<i>of a Southern way of life.</i>

1:23:21.497 --> 1:23:22.873
<i>Well, look at what</i>
<i>the Northerners</i>

1:23:22.873 --> 1:23:26.168
<i>are fighting for.</i>

1:23:26.168 --> 1:23:28.587
<i>Think about all those people.</i>

1:23:28.587 --> 1:23:30.839
<i>They're fighting</i>
<i>for this idea.</i>

1:23:30.839 --> 1:23:32.466
<i>The nation is new.</i>

1:23:32.466 --> 1:23:35.177
<i>We're largely</i>
<i>made up of immigrants.</i>

1:23:35.177 --> 1:23:36.678
<i>They have come here</i>
<i>because they've seen</i>

1:23:36.678 --> 1:23:38.722
<i>what it's like</i>
<i>in the Old World.</i>

1:23:38.722 --> 1:23:41.683
<i>And that idea that</i>
<i>all men are created equal...</i>

1:23:41.683 --> 1:23:45.103
<i>if it doesn't exist here,</i>
<i>it doesn't exist anywhere.</i>

1:23:45.103 --> 1:23:49.024
<i>And therefore,</i>
<i>they're willing to fight.</i>

1:23:49.024 --> 1:23:52.027
[soldiers cheering]

1:23:52.027 --> 1:23:56.490
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:23:56.490 --> 1:24:00.077
<i>‐ The greatest enthusiasm</i>
<i>was inspired by the fact</i>

1:24:00.077 --> 1:24:02.079
<i>that the movement was south.</i>

1:24:02.079 --> 1:24:03.956
‐ Headed to Richmond!

1:24:03.956 --> 1:24:05.541
‐ We're going south, boys!

1:24:05.541 --> 1:24:08.877
<i>‐ It indicated to the men</i>
<i>that they had passed through</i>

1:24:08.877 --> 1:24:13.340
<i>the beginning of the end.</i>

1:24:13.340 --> 1:24:16.385
<i>There would be</i>
<i>no turning back.</i>

1:24:16.385 --> 1:24:19.721
<i>♪ ♪</i>

1:24:19.721 --> 1:24:22.099
‐ Advance!

1:24:22.099 --> 1:24:24.893
<i>‐ Hold on with a bulldog grip.</i>

1:24:24.893 --> 1:24:27.604
Chew and choke
as much as possible.

1:24:27.604 --> 1:24:29.982
<i>‐ We've got Lee</i>
<i>in a box, General.</i>

1:24:29.982 --> 1:24:31.441
‐ Go after him.

1:24:31.441 --> 1:24:33.193
<i>I regard it as my duty</i>

1:24:33.193 --> 1:24:35.112
<i>by asking of you</i>
<i>the surrender</i>

1:24:35.112 --> 1:24:37.322
<i>of the Confederate States</i>
<i>Army.</i>

1:24:37.322 --> 1:24:40.450
President Lincoln
has been shot.

1:24:40.450 --> 1:24:41.910
<i>‐ The country</i>
<i>having just emerged</i>

1:24:41.910 --> 1:24:43.245
<i>from a great rebellion,</i>

1:24:43.245 --> 1:24:45.747
<i>I ask patient forbearance,</i>

1:24:45.747 --> 1:24:49.418
<i>one toward another,</i>
<i>cementing a happy union.</i>
